{"title_page": "Coal in Turkey", "text_new": "{{Use European English|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Coal mining, power, industry, and its health and environmental problems in the Eurasian country}}\n[[File:TKI Dragline.JPG|thumb|State-owned lignite company [[Turkish Coal Operations Authority]] dragline in Yenik\u00f6y, [[Milas]]]]\n\n[[Coal]] supplied over a quarter of [[Energy in Turkey|Turkey's primary energy]] from the 1990s to the 2010s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/countries/turkey|title=Total primary energy supply (TPES) by source, Turkey|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The heavily [[energy subsidies#Turkey|subsidised]] coal industry generates over a third of the [[Electricity sector in Turkey|country's electricity]]<ref name=\"MinEn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal|title=Coal|publisher=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917110843/http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal|archive-date=17 September 2018|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> and emits a third of  [[greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey|Turkey's greenhouse gases]]. Every year, thousands of people die prematurely from coal-related causes, the most common of which is [[Air pollution in Turkey|local air pollution]].\n\nMost coal mined in Turkey is [[lignite]] (brown coal), which is more polluting than other types of coal.<ref name=HEAL2018>{{cite web |title=Lignite coal \u2013 health effects and recommendations from the health sector |url=https://www.env-health.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/HEAL-Lignite-Briefing-en_web.pdf |publisher=Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL) |date=December 2018 |access-date=2019-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211010345/https://www.env-health.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/HEAL-Lignite-Briefing-en_web.pdf |archive-date=2018-12-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>  [[Energy policy of Turkey|Turkey's energy policy]] encourages mining lignite for [[List of coal-fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations]] in order to reduce [[Energy in Turkey#Gas|gas imports]];<ref name=\"MinEn\" /> and coal supplies over 40% of domestic energy production.<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 5</ref> Mining peaked in 2018, at over 100 million tonnes,<ref name=\"AA1\">{{cite news |title=Turkey breaks local coal production record in 2018 |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-breaks-local-coal-production-record-in-2018/1366302 |agency=Anadolu Agency |date=16 January 2019 |access-date=2 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203085042/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-breaks-local-coal-production-record-in-2018/1366302 |archive-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and declined considerably in 2019.<ref name=\":0\" /> Almost all local coal is lignite, whereas Turkey imports almost all of the [[bituminous coal]] it uses. The largest coalfield in Turkey is [[Elbistan coalfield|Elbistan]].<ref name=\"HDN1\">{{cite news |title=Turkey transfers operating rights of seven coal fields to private companies |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-transfers-operating-rights-of-seven-coal-fields-to-private-companies-137794 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=12 October 2018 |access-date=12 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012103505/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-transfers-operating-rights-of-seven-coal-fields-to-private-companies-137794 |archive-date=12 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Zonguldak TTK liman\u0131.jpg|thumb|Wharf that formerly shipped coal out of Zonguldak]]\n[[File:Ottoman submarine Abdulhamid 1886.jpg|thumb|Coal-fired [[Ottoman submarine Abd\u00fcl Hamid]], built in 1886]]\nAs the [[List of major surface ships of the Ottoman steam navy|Ottoman Navy expanded its steam powered fleet]] in the 1840s it was important to find domestic coalfields, to help defend the [[Ottoman Empire]] against the expanding [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\":3\" /> There are several stories, probably untrue, about the discovery of coal on the [[Black Sea]] coast in what is now  [[Zonguldak Province]]: but historians know that the Ere\u011fli Coal Mine Company started production in 1842 and that coal mined in [[Karadeniz Ere\u011fli|Ere\u011fli]] and [[Amasra]] was used to fuel steamboats.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Ayhan |first1=Arda |title=The History of Coal in Turkey and the Story of its Origins |url=http://www.miningturkeymag.com/pdfler/mak-1466845656.pdf |accessdate=30 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005026/http://www.miningturkeymag.com/pdfler/mak-1466845656.pdf |archive-date=1 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1848 the Ere\u011fli Coal Basin (now called the [[Zonguldak basin|Zonguldak Basin]]) was mapped and claimed by [[Abdulmejid I|Sultan Abdulmejid I]], who later leased it, mainly to foreign merchants.<ref name=\":3\" /> The first customer of Turkey's coal industry was the [[Ottoman Navy]], but for the [[Crimean War]] in the mid-1850s production was commandeered by their allies, the [[Royal Navy#1815\u20131914|British Royal Navy]],<ref name=\":3\" /> and production increased by importing mining machinery and training Turkish miners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/en/download/article-file/44295|title=Underground mining operations in Zonguldak coal mines|last=G\u00fcney|first=Mehmet|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> By 1875 the Ottoman Navy had become the third largest in the world and expansion of the mines attracted workers from outside the area, despite the dangerous conditions.<ref>{{Citation|last=\u015eeng\u00fcl|first=H. Tar\u0131k|title=Zonguldak Coalfield and the Past and Future of Turkish Coal-mining Communities|date=2012|work=Changing Work and Community Identities in European Regions: Perspectives on the Past and Present|pages=154\u2013183|editor-last=Kirk|editor-first=John|series=Identity Studies in the Social Sciences|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|language=en|doi=10.1057/9780230353916_6|isbn=9780230353916|last2=Aytekin|first2=E. Attila|editor2-last=Contrepois|editor2-first=Sylvie|editor3-last=Jefferys|editor3-first=Steve}}</ref>\n \nThe first power station [[Silahtara\u011fa Power Station]] (now  [[SantralIstanbul]] culture center) opened in 1914, and after the defeat of the empire in [[World War I]], and the subsequent [[Turkish War of Independence]], the new Republic of Turkey [[Atat\u00fcrk's Reforms#Industry|industrialized further as part of Atat\u00fcrk's reforms]]. Lignite from Soma supplied the army in WW1<ref name=\":3\" /> and lignite mining began at several other coalfields in 1927.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atalay|first=Figen|date=2015|title=The History of the Coal Mining Industry and Mining Accidents in the World and Turkey|journal=Turkish Thoracic Journal|volume=16|issue=Suppl 1|pages=S5\u2013S8|doi=10.5152/ttd.2015.002|issn=2148-7197|pmc=5783104|pmid=29404107}}</ref> But Zonguldak remains the only national source of the hard coal which was necessary for steelmaking: its mines were [[nationalization|nationalized]] in 1940.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesis.bilkent.edu.tr/0001720.pdf|title=Workers of the Ere\u011fli\u0307-Zonguldak Coal Basin, 1848-1922|last=Aytekin|first=Erden Attila|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the mid-20th century the state encouraged the growth of [[cement]]<ref name=\":3\" /> and steelmaking in Zonguldak; and in the late 20th century many power stations were constructed near lignite fields such as [[Elbistan coalfield]].\n\nIn the early 21st century there was a growing realisation of coal's damage to health, but the state wished to avoid importing too much natural gas, which was expensive at that time: the nascent environmental movement was unable to prevent many more coal-fired power stations being built. After years of struggle by environmentalists flue emissions standards were finally improved at the end of the 2010s, resulting in the closure of a few older plants. As for [[steelmaking]], most plants are now [[electric arc furnace]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cib.org.tr/en/statistics.html|title=STATISTICS|website=Turkish Steel|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Coalfields and mines==\n{{See also|Category:Coal mines in Turkey}}\nDue to the country's geology, coal mines must reach very deep to obtain coal of decent quality.<ref name=GBR/> In 2017 almost half of the coal was mined by the state but the government wishes to privatize more.<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 8</ref> As of 2019, there are 436 [[coal mining]] companies,<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 3</ref> 740 coal mines,<ref>{{cite news |title=Coal mine collapses in Turkey |url=https://en.trend.az/world/turkey/3021127.html |agency=Trend |date=18 February 2019 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013429/https://en.trend.az/world/turkey/3021127.html |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and more mining and exploration licences are being tendered.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tender announcements |url=http://mapeg.gov.tr/Ihaleler.aspx |publisher=MAPEG |accessdate=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190225044828/http://mapeg.gov.tr/Ihaleler.aspx |archive-date=25 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, some drilling companies are not bidding for licences because mineral exploration is more profitable.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=38 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018 many mining licences were combined.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=37 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mining is documented in the \"e-maden\" computer system (\"maden\" means \"mine\" in Turkish).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjiportali.com/mapeg-bazi-islemleri-sadece-e-maden-portali-uzerinden-kabul-edecek/|title=MAPEG, Baz\u0131 \u0130\u015flemleri Sadece E-Maden Portal\u0131 \u00dczerinden Kabul Edecek!|date=2019-12-12|website=Enerji Portal\u0131|language=tr|access-date=2020-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128085419/https://www.enerjiportali.com/mapeg-bazi-islemleri-sadece-e-maden-portali-uzerinden-kabul-edecek/|archive-date=2020-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Coal miners do not have the right to [[Strike action|strike]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tr.usembassy.gov/2019-country-reports-on-human-rights-practices-turkey/|title=2019 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices: Turkey|date=2020-03-12|website=U.S. Embassy & Consulates in Turkey|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Hard coal===\nThe [[Zonguldak basin]] in the northwest is the only coal mining region in Turkey that produces hard coal:{{refn|group=note|[[Bituminous coal]] is called hardcoal (ta\u015fk\u00f6m\u00fcr in Turkish) in the [[International Energy Agency]] document for Turkey and anthracite in Turkish government documents. On Wikipedia, ''hardcoal'' redirects to [[anthracite]].}} about 2 million tons a year<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/enerji-piyasalarinda-2020-yili-ongoruleri-31771yy.htm|title=Enerji piyasalar\u0131nda 2020 y\u0131l\u0131 \u00f6ng\u00f6r\u00fcleri|last=Di\u0307reskeneli\u0307|first=Haluk|date=2020-01-03|website=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> from mines including [[Armut\u00e7uk coal mine|Kandilli]], [[Amasra]], [[Karadon coal mine|Karadon]], [[Kozlu coal mine|Kozlu]] and [[\u00dcz\u00fclmez coal mine|\u00dcz\u00fclmez]].<ref name=Mills2014/> Compared to other countries, the [[Energy value of coal|energy value of the coal]] is low, at {{convert|4,000|kcal/kg|kcal/lb}} to {{convert|6,000|kcal/kg|kcal/lb|abbr=on}}. Although low grade it is generally [[Coke (fuel)|cokeable]] or semi-cokeable quality.<ref name=Esmaeili2018>{{cite web |title=Carbon Capture, Utilization and Storage in the Context of Turkish Energy Market |url=https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |publisher=IICEC |date=June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181030/https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Mills2014>{{cite web |title=Prospects for coal and clean coal technologies in Turkey |url=https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |publisher=IEACCC |date=July 2014 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181742/https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Long-wall mining]] is necessary due to the tectonic structure of the seams.<ref name=GBR/>\n\n===Lignite===\nThe  most significant deposits are [[Neogene]] period,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Coal Deposits of Turkey: Properties and Importance on Energy Demand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259563494_Coal_deposits_of_Turkey_properties_and_importance_on_energy_demand|journal=Bulletin of the Geological Society of Greece|volume=|pages=}}</ref> and in 2018 Turkey was the third-largest lignite mining country,<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 7</ref> with 7% of world production.<ref name=HEAL2018/> Almost half of the country's lignite reserves are in the [[Elbistan coalfield|Af\u015fin\u2013Elbistan basin]].<ref name=\"MinEn\" /> Lignite coalfields include [[Elbistan coalfield|Elbistan]], Kutahya Tavsanl\u0131, Inez, [[Manisa]], \u0130na\u011fz\u0131-Ba\u011fl\u0131k and [[Gediz, K\u00fctahya|Gediz]].<ref name=\"SPG2018\">{{cite news |title=Turkish government to transfer 203 million mt of coal reserves to private owners |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/101218-turkish-government-to-transfer-203-million-mt-of-coal-reserves-to-private-owners |publisher=S & P Global |date=12 Oct 2018 |access-date=16 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016165428/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/101218-turkish-government-to-transfer-203-million-mt-of-coal-reserves-to-private-owners |archive-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Mills2014/>  Locations of major individual lignite mines include [[Tun\u00e7bilek power station|Tun\u00e7bilek]] in [[Tav\u015fanl\u0131]], [[Yata\u011fan, Mu\u011fla|Yata\u011fan]] near the southern [[Aegean Sea]], [[Yenik\u00f6y power station|Yenik\u00f6y]] in [[Mu\u011fla Province|Mu\u011fla]] and [[Seyit\u00f6mer power station|Seyit\u00f6mer]] in [[K\u00fctahya]]; and there is a [[gilsonite]] mine in [[Silopi]].<ref name=Mills2014/> Turkish lignite has high carbon,{{refn|group=note|The [[Heat of combustion#Lower heating value|net calorific value]] of Turkish lignite is lower than that of typical lignite,<ref>Turkstat report (2020), p. 50</ref> varying by power station; its average is about 2,800|kcal/kg.<ref name=SETA2019>{{cite web |title=Yerli\u0307 ve mi\u0307lli\u0307 enerji\u0307 poli\u0307ti\u0307kalari ekseni\u0307nde k\u00f6m\u00fcr |url=https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |publisher=SETAV |accessdate=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214061430/https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The average carbon content of lignite in Turkey is higher than that of typical lignite, measured at 30.5 kg/GJ in 2018.<ref>Turkstat report (2020), p. 50</ref>}} sulphur, ash, moisture and volatile components.\n<ref name=Esmaeili2018>{{cite web |title=Carbon Capture, Utilization and Storage in the Context of Turkish Energy Market |url=https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |publisher=IICEC |date=June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181030/https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Mills2014>{{cite web |title=Prospects for coal and clean coal technologies in Turkey |url=https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |publisher=IEACCC |date=July 2014 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181742/https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Mining Technology===\nExploration and research is done by Maden Tetkik Arama Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc (MTA).<ref name=\":2\" />  In the 2010s coal mining technology from China was imported.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=35 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> But according to energy analyst Haluk Direskeneli coal power plant technology which has been imported is unsuitable for Turkish coal, so [[refractory]] distortions are occurring, and [[control system]]s and other equipment is failing. He says that [[circulating fluidized bed]] (CFB) technology is unsuitable because Turkish lignite does not burn continuously in the CFB combustion chamber without supplementary liquid fuel. In Direskeneli's opinion \"local coal enters the combustion chamber as ice in winter and as mud in summer\", so the water content of domestic coal should be reduced by preheating.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurasiareview.com/02122019-turkey-energy-and-infrastructure-forecast-2020-oped/|title=Turkey: Energy And Infrastructure Forecast 2020 \u2013 OpEd|last=Direskeneli|first=Haluk|date=2019-12-02|website=Eurasia Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204173245/https://www.eurasiareview.com/02122019-turkey-energy-and-infrastructure-forecast-2020-oped/|archive-date=2019-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, environmental regulations for coal mines still lag behind international standards despite improvements.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=33|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|2019}} an expansion of coal washing capacity was planned together with research on [[coal pollution mitigation]] and lignite [[gasification]].<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 15</ref>\n\n==Health and safety==\n\nThe Istanbul Policy Center estimates that, every year, coal causes at least 2,800 premature deaths, 637,000 working days to be lost, and 3.6 billion euros in additional costs. Although there are some concerns about ground{{refn|group=note|[[Fly ash]], a byproduct of the coal refining process, is often sold to cement factories as a raw material.<ref name=HEAL2018/> Concentrations of natural [[radionuclides]] vary depending on the power station and the product may be safe in building materials depending on the amount used.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ozden |first1=Banu |last2=G\u00fcler |first2=Erkan |last3=Vaasma |first3=Taavi |last4=Horv\u00e1th |first4=M\u00e1ria |last5=Kiisk |first5=Madis |last6=Kov\u00e1cs |first6=Tibor |title=Enrichment of naturally occurring radionuclides and trace elements in Yatagan and Yenikoy coal-fired thermal power plants, Turkey |journal=Journal of Environmental Radioactivity |date=August 2018 |volume=188 |pages=100\u2013107 |doi=10.1016/j.jenvrad.2017.09.016 |pmid=28965987 }}</ref>}} and water<ref>{{Cite journal|last=U\u00e7ar|first=Ali|last2=\u015eens\u00f6\u011f\u00fct|first2=Cem|last3=Ediz|first3=\u0130 G\u00f6ktay|date=2019-01-05|title=Invest\u0131gat\u0131on for Env\u0131ronmental Effects and Evaluat\u0131on of F\u0131ne Ta\u0131l\u0131ngs from Tuncb\u0131lek Coal Process\u0131ng Plant/Turkey|url=http://econ-environ-geol.org/index.php/ojs/article/view/12|journal=International Journal of Economic and Environmental Geology|language=en|pages=28\u201334|issn=2223-957X}}</ref> pollution; [[particulates]], which are microscopic airborne particles, cause most coal-related deaths by worsening [[air pollution in Turkey]].<ref name=HEAL2018/>\n\n===Workers' health and safety===\nAfter the deaths of over 300 people in the [[Soma mine disaster]] in 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkey-rights-violations-found-in-mine-disaster-case/1759720|title=Turkey: Rights violations found in mine disaster case|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> new health and safety regulations were introduced. {{As of|2018}}, most mining accidents happen in coal mines but the reasons for Turkey's poor mining safety are not entirely clear.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=14\u201315 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> The government has restricted access to workplace accident statistics, but coal mining is thought to be the most accident-prone sector of the economy.<ref name=HEAL2018/> {{As of|2018|}} coal mining fatalities continue to occur in [[Illegal mining|illegal mines]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Two workers killed in illegal mine collapse in Turkey's Zonguldak |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/two-workers-killed-in-illegal-mine-collapse-in-turkeys-zonguldak-134293 |agency=H\u00fcrriyet |date=8 July 2018 |access-date=31 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231194036/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/two-workers-killed-in-illegal-mine-collapse-in-turkeys-zonguldak-134293 |archive-date=31 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Coal miners suffer respiratory diseases such as [[Coalworker's pneumoconiosis|black lung]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ghs.asyod.org/Konular/2019-2-19.pdf|title=Coal Worker's Pneumoconiosis|last=ERBOY|first=Fatma|date=|website=|publisher=Zonguldak Kara Elmas \u00dcniversitesi T\u0131p Fak\u00fcltesi, G\u00f6\u011f\u00fcs Hastal\u0131klar\u0131 Ana Bilim Dal\u0131, Zonguldak|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127152227/http://ghs.asyod.org/Konular/2019-2-19.pdf|archive-date=2020-01-27|access-date=}}</ref>, [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]],<ref name=\":4\" /> [[back pain]],<ref>{{cite journal |title=Low back pain and lumbar angles in Turkish coal miners |journal=American Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=50 |issue=2 |pages=92\u201396 |doi=10.1002/ajim.20417 |pmid=17238134 |url=https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/biblio/20885715 |year=2007 |last1=Sarikaya |first1=Selda |last2=\u00d6zdolap |first2=\u015eenay |last3=G\u00fcm\u00fc\u015ftas\u015f |first3=\u015eenol |last4=Ko\u00e7 |first4=\u00dclk\u00fc |access-date=2018-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027185620/https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/biblio/20885715 |archive-date=2018-10-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[periodontal disease]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=\u0130nan\u00e7 Cengiz |first1=Murat |last2=Zengin |first2=B\u00fc\u015fra |last3=\u0130\u00e7en |first3=Murat |last4=K\u00f6kt\u00fcrk |first4=Fir\u00fczan |title=Prevalence of periodontal disease among mine workers of Zonguldak, Kozlu District, Turkey: a cross-sectional study |journal=BMC Public Health |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=361 |date=2018 |doi=10.1186/s12889-018-5304-1 |pmid=29548308 |pmc=5857090 }}</ref> and other illnesses; and increased risk from [[respiratory infections]] such as [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/04/turkey-coronavirus-coal-mines-pollution-dirty-air-zonguldak.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak exposes health risks of coal rush|last=Ugurtas|first=Selin|date=2020-04-17|website=Al-Monitor|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> \n\n===Air pollution===\n[[File:Yenik\u00f6y Power Plant Milas Mu\u011fla Turkey.jpg|thumb|[[Yenik\u00f6y power station]] in [[Milas]], [[Mu\u011fla Province|Mu\u011fla]]]]\n{{See also|Air pollution in Turkey}}\nAir pollution from some large coal-fired power stations is publicly visible in [[Sentinel-5 Precursor|Sentinel satellite]] data.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polluters exposed by new eye in the sky satellite |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-44705268 |date=5 July 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152552/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-44705268 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TROPOMI Level 2 data products |url=http://www.tropomi.eu/data-products/level-2-products |publisher=KNMI R&D Satellite Observations |accessdate=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152638/http://www.tropomi.eu/data-products/level-2-products |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) says that old coal-fired power stations and residential heating are emitting dangerous levels of fine particulates: so it recommends reducing particulate emissions by replacing coal used for residential heating with gas, and retrofitting or closing old coal-fired power plants.<ref>OECD (2019), p. 20</ref> Although the Turkish government receives reports of measurements of air pollution from the smokestacks of individual coal-fired power stations, it does not publish the reports, unlike the EU. The OECD has also recommended Turkey create and publish a [[pollutant release and transfer register]].<ref>OECD (2019), p. 30</ref>\n\nFlue gas emission limits in milligrams per cubic metre (mg/Nm<sup>3</sup>) are:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea-coal.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Turkey-emissions-standard.pdf|title=Emission standards: Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Sanayi\u0307 Kaynakli Hava Ki\u0307rli\u0307li\u0307\u011fi\u0307ni\u0307n Kontrol\u00fc Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307\u011fi\u0307nde De\u011fi\u0307\u015fi\u0307kli\u0307k Yapilmasina Dai\u0307r Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307k |journal=Resm\u00ee Gazete |date=20 December 2014 |issue=29211 |page=Appx 1 page 15 |url=http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2014/12/20141220-2.htm |access-date=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227034715/http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2014/12/20141220-2.htm |archive-date=27 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Size of power station     !! Dust !! [[Sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]] !! [[Nitrogen dioxide|NO<sub>2</sub>]] !! [[Carbon monoxide|CO]]\n|-\n| 0.5 MW \u2264 capacity < 5 MW  || 200  || see cited source                  ||  see cited source                   || 200\n|-\n| 5 MW \u2264 capacity   < 50 MW || 150  || see cited source                  ||  see cited source                   || 200\n|-\n| 50 MW \u2264 capacity < 100 MW ||  50  ||                               850 || 400                                 || 150\n|-\n| capacity         \u2265 100 MW ||  30  ||                               200 || 200                                 || 200\n|-\n|}\n\n(see cited source for more details, such as some SO<sub>2</sub> exceptions) and some plants lack [[electrostatic precipitator]] filters.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Environment Minister]] Murat Kurum said in December 2019 that unless plants which emit over the limits start installing the necessary filters during the first half of 2020 they will face fines, nationalization or closure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-dunya-50653983|title=Erdo\u011fan'\u0131n veto karar\u0131n\u0131n alt\u0131nda ne yat\u0131yor?|last=Say\u0131n|first=Ay\u015fe|date=2019-12-04|work=[[BBC]]|access-date=2019-12-05|language=tr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205034739/https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-dunya-50653983|archive-date=2019-12-05|url-status=live}}</ref> The limits are laxer than the EU [[Industrial Emissions Directive]] and the [[Sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]] limit for large coal-fired power plants in other countries, such as India at 100&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup>, and China at 35&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenpeace.org/international/press-release/23819/global-so2-air-pollution-hotspots-ranked-by-greenpeace-analysis|title=Greenpeace analysis ranks global SO2 air pollution hotspots|website=Greenpeace International|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901063929/https://www.greenpeace.org/international/press-release/23819/global-so2-air-pollution-hotspots-ranked-by-greenpeace-analysis/|archive-date=2019-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, air pollution in districts that are near coal-fired power stations greatly exceeds national limits of PM10 (coarse particulate matter) and SO<sub>2</sub>. In [[Elbistan]] district, PM10 averages are over three times the regulatory limit, and in [[Soma, Manisa|Soma]] SO<sub>2</sub> averages are over four times the limit.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hava Kirlili\u011fi ve Sa\u011fl\u0131k Etkileri Kara Rapor |date=11 May 2019 |pages=52\u201353 |url=https://www.temizhavahakki.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Hava-Kirlilig%CC%86i-ve-Sag%CC%86l%C4%B1k-Etkileri-Kara-Rapor-2019.pdf |access-date=11 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606182418/https://www.temizhavahakki.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Hava-Kirlili%C4%9Fi-ve-Sa%C4%9Fl%C4%B1k-Etkileri-Kara-Rapor-2019.pdf |archive-date=6 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, according to [[Greenpeace]] air pollution around power plants in [[K\u00fctahya Province]] was three times higher than [[World Health Organisation]] recommended limits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/environment/turkish-minister-says-coal-plants-must-start-using-pollution-filters-6-months|title=Turkish minister says coal plants must start using pollution filters in 6 months|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204062736/https://ahvalnews.com/environment/turkish-minister-says-coal-plants-must-start-using-pollution-filters-6-months|archive-date=2019-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\n\n===Greenhouse gas emissions===\n{{See also|Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey#Coal}}\n[[File:Fossil fuel CO2 Turkey.svg|thumb|CO2 from burning fossil fuels]]\n[[File:Ghg pie chart Turkey 2018.svg|thumb|Greenhouse gas emissions in 2018]]\nCoal combustion emitted over 150{{Spaces}}Mt of [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] in total in 2018,{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2020|p=57}} about a third of Turkey's greenhouse gas.{{efn|1=29% of the 521 Mt gross emissions in 2018 or 35% of the 426 Mt net emissions}} Emissions from individual power plants over 20 MW are measured.<ref>{{Cite web|title=ETS Detailed Information: Turkey|url=https://icapcarbonaction.com/en/?option=com_etsmap&task=export&format=pdf&layout=list&systems%5B%5D=66|website=International Carbon Action Partnership|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[life-cycle greenhouse-gas emissions of energy sources|Life-cycle emissions]] of Turkish coal-fired power stations are over 1 kg [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2</sub>eq]] per kilowatt-hour.<ref name=\"Atilgan\">{{cite journal |last1=Atilgan |first1=Burcin |last2=Azapagic |first2=Adisa |title=An integrated life cycle sustainability assessment of electricity generation in Turkey |journal=Energy Policy |date=2016 |volume=93 |page=177|doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2016.02.055 |doi-access=free }}</ref> The [[environmental impact assessment]] (EIA) for the proposed [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station]] [[Fossil fuel power station#Estimation of carbon dioxide emissions|estimated {{CO2}} emissions]] would be more than 60&nbsp;million tonnes of {{CO2}} per year.{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=319|quote = Atmosfere Verilecek CO2 Miktar\u0131: ....... = 61.636.279,98 tCO2/y\u0131l\" means \"Amount of CO2 which will be emitted to the atmosphere: ....... = 61,636,279.98 tCO2/year\"}} By comparison, total annual [[greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey]] are about 520&nbsp;million tonnes;<ref name=\"Anadolu1\">{{cite news|quote = Turkey's total greenhouse gas emissions in 2018 ..... equivalent to 520.9 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2). |publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/life/environment/turkeys-greenhouse-gas-emissions-fall-for-second-year-in-a-row|title=Turkey's greenhouse gas emissions fall for second year in a row|date=2020-03-31|work=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> thus more than a tenth of greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey would be from the planned power station.{{refn|group=note|62 megatonnes would be emitted annually{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=319|quote = Atmosfere Verilecek CO2 Miktar\u0131: ....... = 61.636.279,98 tCO2/y\u0131l\" means \"Amount of CO2 which will be emitted to the atmosphere: ....... = 61,636,279.98 tCO2/year\"}} if run at the targeted [[capacity factor]], whereas Turkey's current annual emissions are 521 megatonnes.<ref name=\"Anadolu1\"/> [[Wikipedia:No original research#Routine calculations|By simple arithmetic]] 62 megatonnes is more than 10% of 521+62 megatonnes.}}{{refn|group=note|On average somewhat over a million tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> was emitted for every [[TWh]] of electricity generated in Turkey by coal-fired power stations in 2010.{{sfnp|Atilgan et al|2016|p=177}} This power station aims to generate just over 12.5 TWh (gross) per year.{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=xix|quote = \"y\u0131ll\u0131k ortalama br\u00fct 12.506 GWh, net 11.380 GWh enerji \u00fcretimi hedeflenmektedir.\" means \"targeted annual generation is 12,506 GWh gross, 11,380 GWh net\"}} The calculation in the EIA assumes an emission factor of 94.6 tCO2/TJ,{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=319}} which is three times the average of 31 for Turkish lignite,{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2020|p=50}} but it is unclear whether this is the only reason the CO2 emissions per kWh are predicted to be very high compared to the 2010 average. Since 2020, more stringent filtering of local air pollutants from the smokestack has been compulsory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energy/coal/turkey-shuts-power-plants-for-not-installing-filters/27934|title=Turkey shuts power plants for not installing filters|publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Moreover, although the average is about 2800,<ref name=SETA2019>{{cite report|title=Yerli\u0307 ve mi\u0307lli\u0307 enerji\u0307 poli\u0307ti\u0307kalari ekseni\u0307nde k\u00f6m\u00fcr |url=https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |publisher=[[Foundation for Political, Economic and Social Research]]|date=January 2019}}</ref> the [[Heat of combustion#Lower heating value|net calorific value]] of Turkish lignite varies between 1000 and 6000 kcal/kg.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2020|pages=59,60}}}} {{As of|2019}} coal mine methane remains a challenge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unece.org/info/media/news/sustainable-energy/2019/paving-the-way-for-safer-and-greener-coal-mine-methane-management-in-turkey-and-ukraine/doc.html|title=Paving the way for safer and greener coal mine methane management in Turkey and Ukraine|website=www.unece.org|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n===Water consumption===\nSome power stations in Zonguldak and Mu\u011fla consume large quantities of fresh water.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Thermal power plants in Zonguldak and Mu\u011fla leave nearby villages without water in the middle of a pandemic|url=https://www.duvarenglish.com/health-2/coronavirus/2020/04/13/thermal-power-plants-in-zonguldak-and-mugla-leave-nearby-villages-without-water-in-the-middle-of-a-pandemic/|website=www.duvarenglish.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Consumption==\nThe amount of coal consumed in 2017 was more than a quarter higher than the amount in 2012, but coal made up about 30% of Turkey's primary energy in both years.<ref name=ClimateTransparency2019>{{Cite web|url=https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Managing-the-phase-out-of-coal-DIGITAL.pdf|title=Managing the Phase-out of Coal: A Comparison of Actions in G20 Countries|last=|first=|date=May 2019|website=Climate Transparency|access-date=2019-05-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524071757/https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Managing-the-phase-out-of-coal-DIGITAL.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018 [[List of coal-fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] burnt 80% of coal to generate electricity, 14% was used by industry, and 6% by buildings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://estore.enerdata.net/turkey-energy.html|title=Turkey energy market research {{!}} Turkey data, reports, prices|website=estore.enerdata.net|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> In 2018, 13 [[Tonne of oil equivalent|Mtoe]] of hard coal were used to generate electricity and heat; 4 Mtoe, in coke ovens; 2 Mtoe, for home heating; 2 Mtoe, in cement manufacture; and 1 Mtoe was used for iron and steel.<ref name=\"Energy Administration (2018)\">Energy Administration (2018)</ref> In 2018, 12 Mtoe of lignite were used to generate electricity and heat, 2 Mtoe in industry, and 1 Mtoe was used for home heating.<ref name=\"Energy Administration (2018)\" /> Lignite fired power stations did not become more productive between 2009 and 2018,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kasap|first=Ya\u015far|last2=\u015eens\u00f6\u011f\u00fct|first2=Cem|last3=\u00d6ren|first3=\u00d6zer|date=2020-03-01|title=Efficiency change of coal used for energy production in Turkey|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301420719308141|journal=Resources Policy|language=en|volume=65|pages=101577|doi=10.1016/j.resourpol.2019.101577|issn=0301-4207|doi-access=free}}</ref> but three-quarters by weight of coal burnt in Turkish power stations is lignite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yesilgazete.org/blog/2019/10/28/agustos-ayinda-termik-santrallerde-7-milyon-989-bin-ton-komur-yakildi/|title=A\u011fustos ay\u0131nda termik santrallerde 7 milyon 989 bin ton k\u00f6m\u00fcr yak\u0131ld\u0131|last=|first=|date=|website=Ye\u015fil Gazete|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\n==Subsidies==\n{{See also|Electricity sector in Turkey#Economics and finance}}\n\nAs a signatory of the [[Convention on Biological Diversity]] (Aichi Target 3), Turkey committed to phasing out environmentally harmful subsidies, including those to fossil fuels, by 2020.<ref>Doukas (2019), p. 2</ref> But coal remained the most subsidised source of electricity in Turkey.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yildizhan |first1=Hasan |title=Incentive policies for coal plants in Turkey |journal=Thermal Science |date=2017 |volume=21 |issue=5 |pages=1917\u20131924 |doi=10.2298/TSCI160428004Y |doi-access=free }}</ref> By 2020, according to [[Carbon Tracker]], both new wind and solar power were cheaper than building new coal power plants; and they forecast that wind would become cheaper than existing coal plants in 2027, and solar in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Maps_5_Logo.pdf|title=Wind vs Coal Power in Turkey/Solar PV vs Coal in Turkey|last=|first=|date=2020|website=[[Carbon Tracker]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318021148/https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Maps_5_Logo.pdf|archive-date=2020-03-18|access-date=}}</ref> Lignite-fired power stations receive multiple subsidies for construction<ref>{{cite web |title=Investment Guide > Investors' Guide > Incentives |url=http://www.invest.gov.tr/en-US/investmentguide/investorsguide/Pages/Incentives.aspx |website=Invest in Turkey |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019205707/http://www.invest.gov.tr/en-US/investmentguide/investorsguide/Pages/Incentives.aspx |archive-date=19 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{refn|group=note|\"Metals\" described in the 4-b group of Article 2 of the current Mining Law No. 3213 include lignite thus lignite-fired power plants can receive region 5 subsidies regardless of their actual location in Turkey.}} and operation.<ref name=OECD>[http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=FFS_TUR \"Fossil Fuel Support \u2013 TUR\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916205031/https://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=FFS_TUR |date=2018-09-16 }}, OECD, accessed October 2018</ref> Specific subsidy programs include value-added tax waivers, offsetting investment costs and tax reductions.<ref name=TPQ2018>{{cite web |title=A New Strategy for EU-Turkey Energy Cooperation |url=http://turkishpolicy.com/article/938/a-new-strategy-for-eu-turkey-energy-cooperation |publisher=Turkish Policy Quarterly |date=27 November 2018 |access-date=21 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221230735/http://turkishpolicy.com/article/938/a-new-strategy-for-eu-turkey-energy-cooperation |archive-date=21 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Turkey's government support to coal and coal-fired power production and consumption \u20ba millions, 2016\u20132017 annual average <ref>Doukas (2019), p. 2</ref>\n!Instrument\n!Coal production\n!Coal-fired power\n!Coal consumption\n|-\n|Fiscal support (budgetary transfers and tax exemptions)\n|947\n|31\n|1,287\n|-\n|State-owned enterprise investment\n|198\n|953\n|none identified\n|}\n\nIn 2019, the Turkish government supported a bill to subsidize coal mining with multiple economic incentives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-05/18/c_138067631.htm|title=Turkish gov't submits draft bill for recovering incentives \u2013 Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> Mining and coal power plants are funded by the[[Turkey Wealth Fund]], but they do not describe it as a subsidy and they plan to pay dividends to the Treasury by 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/01/21/turkey-wealth-fund-eyes-becoming-strategic-investment-arm-of-the-country|title=Turkey Wealth Fund eyes becoming strategic investment arm of the country|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Sinan|date=2020-01-21|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===Capacity mechanism===\nIn 2019 [[List of power stations in Turkey#Coal|large lignite burning stations were subsidized]]  with [[Electricity market#Capacity market|capacity mechanism payments]] totalling almost 1 billion [[Turkish lira|lira]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/2019da-40-santrale-1-6-milyar-lira-destek-35998h.htm|title=Kapasite mekanizmas\u0131yla 2019\u2019da 40 santrale 1.6 milyar lira \u00f6dendi|date=2020-02-06|website=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milasonder.com/gundem/mucep-mugladaki-tum-termik-santraller-kapatilmalidir/48728|title=MU\u00c7EP: Mu\u011fla\u2019daki t\u00fcm termik santraller kapatilmalidir!|website=www.milasonder.com|language=tr|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204180955/https://www.milasonder.com/gundem/mucep-mugladaki-tum-termik-santraller-kapatilmalidir/48728|archive-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|In the neighbouring EU, by contrast, state aid to new coal power has been banned since 2019 and will be prohibited to existing coal power by 2025.}} Unlike new solar and wind power in Turkey's [[electricity market]], these were not decided by [[reverse auction]] but fixed by the government, and [[energy demand management]] is not eligible.<ref name=\"ResmiGazete30650\">{{cite web|url=http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2019/01/20190109-11.htm|title=Elektri\u0307k Pi\u0307yasasi Kapasi\u0307te Mekani\u0307zmasi Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307\u011fi\u0307nde De\u011fi\u0307\u015fi\u0307kli\u0307k Yapilmasina Dai\u0307r Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307k|date=9 January 2019|publisher=Official Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112143721/http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2019/01/20190109-11.htm|archive-date=12 January 2019|access-date=12 January 2019}}</ref> Subsidy continues in 2020 and 13 coal fired power stations received January payments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjiekonomisi.com/teias-yayinladi-kapasite-mekanizmasi-2020-yili-ocak-ayi-odeme-listesi/11668/|title=TE\u0130A\u015e Yay\u0131nlad\u0131: Kapasite Mekanizmas\u0131 2020 Y\u0131l\u0131 Ocak Ay\u0131 \u00d6deme Listesi|last=|first=|date=|website=Enerji Ekonomisi|language=tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe price of electricity generated from domestic coal is adjusted according to the [[consumer price index]], the [[producer price index]] and the dollar exchange rate, and paid by the [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|state-owned electricity company]] to private-sector power plants.<ref>{{cite news |title=K\u00f6m\u00fcr yerli ama \u00f6demesi dolarla |url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2019/ekonomi/komur-yerli-ama-odemesi-dolarla-3393380/ |work=S\u00f6zc\u00fc |date=5 February 2019 |access-date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214002908/https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2019/ekonomi/komur-yerli-ama-odemesi-dolarla-3393380/ |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Residential heating and cooking===\n[[File:Coal Stove - K\u00f6m\u00fcr Sobas\u0131.JPG|thumb|Coke stove exhibited in Ar\u0131kan House, [[Kozan, Adana|Kozan]].]]\nStarting from the 19th century stoves took the place of wood burning ovens in traditional Anatolian houses: for heating every room had a stove with a stovepipe or chimney. After the late 1970s [[Coke (fuel)|coke]] was reserved for use in institutions such as schools, and the more polluting but cheaper coal was supplied to households.  Imports of natural gas started in the late 1980s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Natural-Gas-Pipelines-and-Projects|title=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources - Natural Gas Pipelines and Projects|website=enerji.gov.tr|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and by the end of the 2010s the pipeline distribution network had been extended to over 80% of the population,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/01/05/total-inflow-to-turkish-gas-system-down-633-in-2019|title=Total inflow to Turkish gas system down 6.33% in 2019|last=AA|first=Daily Sabah with|date=2020-01-05|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> however due to [[energy poverty]] some of those people still used coal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paraanaliz.com/intelligence/household-gas-consumption-slumps-by-12-3-association-blames-it-on-global-warming/|title=Household gas consumption slumps by 12.3%, association blames it on global warming!|last=|first=|date=2019-04-20|website=PAIntelligence|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Thus most buildings constructed since the late 20th century have gas heating not coal. In the 2020s stoves burning coal and wood are still sometimes used for heating especially in rural areas, and even occasionally for cooking<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/messages/downloadsexceeded.html|title=Traditional Cooking Fuels, Ovens & Stoves in Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=citeseerx.ist.psu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> although electricity and bottled gas are available everywhere. Free coal is supplied to households with average per person income less than one third of the minimum wage (less than 700TL in 2020) even in neighbourhoods which have piped gas.<ref>{{Cite web|title=K\u00f6m\u00fcr ve Yakacak Yard\u0131m\u0131 Ba\u015fvurusu Nas\u0131l Yap\u0131l\u0131r? Maddi Yard\u0131m 2020|url=https://www.finans365.com/komur-ve-yakacak-yardimi-basvurusu-nasil-yapilir-maddi-yardim-2020/14657/|last=|first=|date=|website=Finans 365|language=tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref> Indoor concentration of particulates is highest in the winter.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mentese|first=Sibel|last2=Mirici|first2=Nihal A.|last3=Otkun|first3=Muserref T.|last4=Bakar|first4=Coskun|last5=Palaz|first5=Elif|last6=Tasdibi|first6=Deniz|last7=Cevizci|first7=Sibel|last8=Cotuker|first8=Osman|date=2015-11-01|title=Association between respiratory health and indoor air pollution exposure in Canakkale, Turkey|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360132315000347|journal=Building and Environment|series=Special Issue: Indoor pollutants, chemistry and health- Selected papers presented at Indoor Air 2014 conference in Hong Kong|language=en|volume=93|pages=72\u201383|doi=10.1016/j.buildenv.2015.01.023|issn=0360-1323}}</ref> Over three quarters of [[Carbon monoxide poisoning|carbon monoxide deaths]] are due to stoves: almost 200 in 2017 mostly in poorer rural areas.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Can|first=G\u00fcnay|last2=Say\u0131l\u0131|first2=U\u011furcan|last3=Aksu Sayman|first3=\u00d6zden|last4=Kuyumcu|first4=\u00d6mer Faruk|last5=Y\u0131lmaz|first5=Duygu|last6=Esen|first6=Eren|last7=Yurtseven|first7=Eray|last8=Ergin\u00f6z|first8=Ethem|date=2019-01-03|title=Mapping of carbon monoxide related death risk in Turkey: a ten-year analysis based on news agency records|url=https://doi.org/10.1186/s12889-018-6342-4|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=19|issue=1|pages=9|doi=10.1186/s12889-018-6342-4|issn=1471-2458|pmc=6318903|pmid=30606153}}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\n\nBetween 2008 and 2018, coal was partially privatised;<ref name=\"GBR\">{{cite web |title=Turkey's 21st Century Coal Rush |url=https://www.gbreports.com/article/turkeys-21st-century-coal-rush |publisher=Global Business Reports |accessdate=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517131907/https://www.gbreports.com/article/turkeys-21st-century-coal-rush |archive-date=17 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> nevertheless state-owned companies mined over half of the total amount of Turkish coal in that year.<ref name=\"AA1\"/> [[Turkish Coal Operations Authority]] (TK\u0130) owns lignite mines, and [[Turkish Hard Coal Enterprises]] (TTK) owns hardcoal mines.\n\nSeveral companies have acquired mining rights for hard coal fields: Erdemir Madencilik, a subsidiary of Turkey's autonomous military pension program; Oyak; Tumas, a subsidiary of Bereket Holding, and energy company Emsa Enerji.<ref name=\"SPG2018\" /> In 2019 private companies paid over 20 million lira royalties to TTK.<ref>{{Cite web|title='Kara elmas'\u0131 g\u00fcn y\u00fcz\u00fcne \u00e7\u0131karan k\u00f6m\u00fcr firmalar\u0131 TTK'ye de kazand\u0131r\u0131yor|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/ekonomi/kara-elmasi-gun-yuzune-cikaran-komur-firmalari-ttkye-de-kazandiriyor/1821268|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-05-07}}</ref> Lignite fields have been transferred to Imbat Madencilik, Fernas Holding, Demir Export and construction group Yapi Tek.<ref name=GBR/> Another company, Polyak Eynez, is developing a hard lignite mine near \u0130zmir that is planned to be the deepest in the country<ref>{{cite book|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=34|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> and an associated power plant.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://www.finaenerji.com/about-us/ |publisher=Fina Enerji |accessdate=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517145657/https://www.finaenerji.com/about-us/ |archive-date=17 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Eren Holding]] holds the largest amount of coal-fired generation capacity, 2,790 megawatts,<ref>{{cite web |title=Energy |url=http://www.erenholding.com.tr/en/sectors/energy |publisher=Eren Holding |accessdate=27 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228175655/http://www.erenholding.com.tr/en/sectors/energy |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> at the ZETES power complex in Zonguldak. Several companies hold more than a gigawatt of coal power capacity: IC I\u00e7ta\u015f Enerji, the state-owned [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|Electricity Generation Company]] (E\u00dcA\u015e); Konya \u015eeker, a company owned by Anadolu Birlik Holding; ERG Elektrik; Diler Holding; \u00c7elikler Holding and Ciner Holding.<ref name=Carbtrkfullrep2018/> However, mining licence information that is held by the government in the \"e-maden\" database is not released to the public.<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Madenleri olan\" de\u011fil verimli i\u015fleyen kazan\u0131r! |url=https://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/sedat-yilmaz/madenleri-olan-degil-verimli-isleyen-kazanir-27097.html |publisher=Yeni Akit |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111041629/https://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/sedat-yilmaz/madenleri-olan-degil-verimli-isleyen-kazanir-27097.html |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2010s, the government attempted to auction mine licenses to private companies provided that they would build nearby power plants,<ref name=GBR/> but the auctions attracted little interest<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://350.org/sweet-dreams-are-made-of-this-turkeys-coal-to-disagree/|title=Sweet dreams are made of this: Turkey's coal to disagree|website=350.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720143626/https://350.org/sweet-dreams-are-made-of-this-turkeys-coal-to-disagree/|archive-date=2019-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref> as the currency weakened.<ref>{{Cite report|url=https://endcoal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/BoomAndBust_2020_English.pdf|title=Boom and Bust 2020: Tracking the Global Coal Plant Pipeline|last=Shearer|first=Christine|last2=Myllyvirta|first2=Lauri|date=March 2020|publisher=[[Global Energy Monitor]]|url-status=live|last3=Yu|first3=Aiqun|last4=Aitken|first4=Greig|last5=Mathew-Shah|first5=Neha|last6=Dallos|first6=Gyorgy|last7=Nace|first7=Ted}}</ref> Also at that time the government tried to re-privatize the 290-MW Yunus Emre power station, but it remains publicly owned. And although lignite is more polluting than most other types of coal, the government tried to persuade other coal-fired power stations to convert to lignite to reduce import costs.<ref name=SP2019>{{cite news |title=Economic Issues to Weigh on Turkish Market |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/010319-outlook-2019-european-thermal-coal-market-looks-to-china-for-direction-in-year-ahead |publisher=S & P Global: Platts |date=3 January 2019 |access-date=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106153609/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/010319-outlook-2019-european-thermal-coal-market-looks-to-china-for-direction-in-year-ahead |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|2018 Turkish currency crisis]] and 2020 [[coronavirus recession]]{{Citation needed|date=May 2020}} increased costs for mining companies and increased the difficulty of obtaining bank credits, threatening the coal industry.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=9|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Turkish energy companies owe over US$50 billion to banks. In particular, Anadolu Birlik Holding holds $1 billion in debt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-23/turkey-s-anadolu-birlik-said-to-seek-energy-loan-restructuring|title=One of Turkey's Largest Food Producers Seeks Loan Restructuring|date=23 January 2019|access-date=4 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207022445/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-23/turkey-s-anadolu-birlik-said-to-seek-energy-loan-restructuring|archive-date=7 February 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]}}</ref>\n\n===International investments===\n\nTurkish company Y\u0131lmaden has acquired [[Mineral industry of Colombia#Coal|coal mining rights in Colombia]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=58|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Companies based in Turkey are building coal-fired power stations in other countries such as [[Sri Lanka]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/09/29/ceb-strikes-another-blow-at-the-countrys-economy-with-uncessary-power-purchase/|title=A 4th coal power plant for Sri Lanka? \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2019-09-29|website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=2019-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003114015/https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/09/29/ceb-strikes-another-blow-at-the-countrys-economy-with-uncessary-power-purchase/|archive-date=2019-10-03|url-status=live}}</ref> and the national exim bank is still prepared to finance coal power if it is Ultra Super Critical with emissions <750g CO2/kWh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ieefa.org/finance-exiting-coal/|title=Over 100 and counting|website=Institute for Energy Economics & Financial Analysis|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> [[State-owned enterprises of China|Chinese state owned enterprises]] and companies investing in coal power projects<ref>OECD (2019), p. 36</ref> include [[Shanghai Electric Power]], which is the main investor in the [[Emba Hunutlu power station]] under construction in [[Adana Province]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey sees a sudden spike in Chinese investments through 'Belt and Road Initiative' |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2018/06/30/turkey-sees-a-sudden-spike-in-chinese-investments-through-belt-and-road-initiative |work=Daily Sabah |date=30 June 2018 |accessdate=1 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152704/https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2018/06/30/turkey-sees-a-sudden-spike-in-chinese-investments-through-belt-and-road-initiative |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Xinhua\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/23/c_138413218.htm|title=China's power plant project with direct investment in Turkey starts construction|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2019-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925164515/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/23/c_138413218.htm|archive-date=2019-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Imports==\n[[File:Coal Balance Turkey.svg|thumb|Much of the rise in consumption in the 21st century was due to the construction of coastal power stations burning imported hard coal.]]\nIn 2019 about 32 million tonnes was imported,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montelnews.com/en/story/turkey-coal-imports-surge-20-amid-lignite-plant-suspensions/1093459|title=Turkey coal imports surge 20% amid lignite plant suspensions|website=www.montelnews.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> 3% of the world's coal,<ref name=ClimateTransparency2019/> and in 2018 US$4.4 billion was spent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/incentives-to-speed-up-returns-on-turkish-rooftop-solar-150045|title=Incentives to speed up returns on Turkish rooftop solar - Latest News|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221155109/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/incentives-to-speed-up-returns-on-turkish-rooftop-solar-150045|archive-date=2019-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Imported coal generates about a quarter of the nation's electricity:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2020/ekonomi/turkiyenin-komur-aski-bitmiyor-5611118/|title=T\u00fcrkiye'nin k\u00f6m\u00fcr a\u015fk\u0131 bitmiyor|website=www.sozcu.com.tr|language=tr|access-date=2020-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207131713/https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2020/ekonomi/turkiyenin-komur-aski-bitmiyor-5611118/|archive-date=2020-02-07|url-status=live}}</ref> more than local coal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/09/17/turkeys-daily-wind-power-generation-sets-record|title=Turkey's daily wind power generation sets record|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-09-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927124116/https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/09/17/turkeys-daily-wind-power-generation-sets-record|archive-date=2019-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[European Union\u2013Turkey Customs Union|customs union deal with the EU]] includes bilateral trade concessions on coal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Updating customs union with EU is priority: Turkish Finance Minister |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/updating-customs-union-with-eu-is-priority-turkish-finance-minister-141557 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228214042/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/updating-customs-union-with-eu-is-priority-turkish-finance-minister-141557 |archive-date=28 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The largest supplier in 2019 was Colombia with 17.5 Mt followed by Russia with 12.35 Mt.{{Citation needed|date=May 2020}}  Russian coal may become more competitive when improvements to Russia's [[Taman, Russia#Port Taman|Taman Port]] on the Black Sea coast are completed in 2020, or when some contracts expire in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/102119-bearish-mood-for-us-colombian-participants-at-coaltrans-event-sources|title=Bearish mood for US, Colombian participants at Coaltrans event: sources {{!}} S&P Global Platts|date=2019-10-21|website=www.spglobal.com|access-date=2019-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101141938/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/102119-bearish-mood-for-us-colombian-participants-at-coaltrans-event-sources|archive-date=2019-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 the largest supplier of [[Metallurgical coal|coking coal]] was Australia, and [[Coke (fuel)|met coke]] was imported from Russia and China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey boosts imports of coking coal from US, Canada |url=https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/1900507-turkey-boosts-imports-of-coking-coal-from-us-canada |publisher=Argus Media |date=10 May 2019 |access-date=24 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524070027/https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/1900507-turkey-boosts-imports-of-coking-coal-from-us-canada |archive-date=24 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2018}} if the import price of thermal coal is less than 70 US$/tonne ([[free on board|fob]]) the state charges the difference as import duty.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|title=Energy pricing and non-market flows in Turkey's energy sector|last=|first=|date=|website=SHURA Energy Transition Center|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230104503/https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|archive-date=2019-12-30|access-date=}}</ref> {{As of|2020|}} coking coal costs around US$130/tonne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/2090040-atlantic-coking-coal-focus-turns-to-logistics|title=Atlantic coking coal: Focus turns to logistics|date=2020-03-24|website=www.argusmedia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> There are bilateral trade concessions with the EU on coal products.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/business/calculation-customs-duties/rules-origin/customs-unions/turkey-customs-unions-preferential-arrangements_en|title=Turkey : Customs Unions and preferential arrangements|last=Anonymous|date=2016-09-13|website=Taxation and Customs Union - European Commission|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203221841/https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/business/calculation-customs-duties/rules-origin/customs-unions/turkey-customs-unions-preferential-arrangements_en|archive-date=2020-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Anthracite]] coal from [[Donbass]], a region in Ukraine, is exported (allegedly illegally) to Turkey. The anthracite is transported through the Russian ports of [[Azov]] and [[Taganrog]] to the Turkish city of [[Samsun]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Russia's Hybrid Strategy in the Sea of Azov: Divide and Antagonize (Part Two) |url=https://jamestown.org/program/russias-hybrid-strategy-in-the-sea-of-azov-divide-and-antagonize-part-two/ |website=Eurasia Daily Monitor Volume: 16 Issue: 18 |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |accessdate=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213082517/https://jamestown.org/program/russias-hybrid-strategy-in-the-sea-of-azov-divide-and-antagonize-part-two/ |archive-date=13 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n{{As of|2020||df=}} the CEO of the sovereign wealth fund wants to invest in coal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ecffb6d6-4f2c-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|title=Turkey wealth fund chief rebuffs criticism of Erdogan's role|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221142807/https://www.ft.com/content/ecffb6d6-4f2c-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|archive-date=2020-02-21|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> According to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]], Turkey is not facing up to the reality that most coal will have to be left in the ground and risks losing access to international [[Climate Finance|climate finance]] if the country does not quickly schedule an exit from coal.\n\nMany local communities strongly oppose coal power stations<ref>{{Cite book|last=Turhan|first=Ethemcan|url=https://www.oapen.org/download?type=document&docid=1005506|title=Transforming Socio-Natures in Turkey: Landscapes, State and Environmental Movements|last2=\u00d6zkaynak|first2=Beg\u00fcm|last3=Ayd\u0131n|first3=Cem \u0130skender|publisher=|year=2020|isbn=978-0-429-42969-9|location=|pages=}}</ref> and mines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yesilgazete.org/blog/2020/02/05/derekoy-yaylasina-maden-ocagi-girisimi-koyluleri-ayaga-kaldirdi/|title=Derek\u00f6y Yaylas\u0131'na maden oca\u011f\u0131 giri\u015fimi k\u00f6yl\u00fcleri aya\u011fa kald\u0131rd\u0131|date=2020-02-05|website=Ye\u015fil Gazete - ekolojik, politik, kat\u0131l\u0131mc\u0131, \u015fenlikli...|language=tr-TR|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> for example by legal action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.korfezgazete.com/hataydaki-cevre-koruma-dernekleri-305-maden-sahasinin-iptalini-talep-etti/|title=Hatay'daki \u00c7evre Koruma Dernekleri 305 Maden Sahas\u0131n\u0131n \u0130ptalini Talep Etti {{!}} K\u00f6rfez Gazetesi|last=Haber|first=Korfezgazete|language=tr|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> From the late 2000s, residents of Amasra strongly fought against the establishment of a coal-fired power station near the city and it was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Regional Briefings for the 2018 Coal Plant Developers List |url=https://coalexit.org/sites/default/files/inline-files/Regional%20Briefings%20CPDL_10-04-2018_final.pdf |work=Coalexit |date=2018 |access-date=2018-12-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412013642/https://coalexit.org/sites/default/files/inline-files/Regional%20Briefings%20CPDL_10-04-2018_final.pdf |archive-date=2019-04-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Alpu]] district, locals of the region won a court battle in 2018 to prevent the building of a new coal mine; the 14th chamber of the [[Council of State (Turkey)|Council of State]] ruled that the mine could only be built with an environmental report.<ref>{{cite news |title=Court says 'environment report necessary' for planned coal mine in western Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/court-says-environment-report-necessary-for-planned-new-coal-mine-in-western-turkey-135665 |work=Demir\u00f6ren News Agency |date=10 August 2018 |access-date=26 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016164949/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/court-says-environment-report-necessary-for-planned-new-coal-mine-in-western-turkey-135665 |archive-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkish activists have also taken their campaign to international conferences.<ref>{{cite news |title=Climate change: Governments don't act? We do! |url=https://www.dw.com/en/climate-change-governments-dont-act-we-do/a-46744981 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=14 December 2018 |access-date=18 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219000851/https://www.dw.com/en/climate-change-governments-dont-act-we-do/a-46744981 |archive-date=19 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nevertheless, in 2019 only 36 of the 600 members of [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|parliament]] voted to reduce power plant emission limits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birgun.net/haber/termik-santrallarin-gercek-bedeli-olum-277431|title=Termik santrallar\u0131n ger\u00e7ek bedeli \u00f6l\u00fcm|website=birgun.net|language=Turkish|access-date=2020-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131110419/https://www.birgun.net/haber/termik-santrallarin-gercek-bedeli-olum-277431|archive-date=2020-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Coal phase-out ==\n\nFive old plants ([[Af\u015fin-Elbistan power stations|Af\u015fin-Elbistan A]], [[Seyit\u00f6mer power station|Seyit\u00f6mer]], Tun\u00e7bilek, [[Kangal power station|Kangal]] and  \u00c7atala\u011fz\u0131) were closed in 2020 because they did not meet new pollution limits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-turkiye-50969252|title=Filtre takt\u0131rmayan ve baca gaz\u0131 ar\u0131tma \u00f6nlemi almayan 5 termik santral tamamen kapat\u0131ld\u0131|date=2020-01-02|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112085934/https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-turkiye-50969252|archive-date=2020-01-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The country is the world's ninth-largest consumer of coal, similar to Poland and Germany, but Germany has more developed plans for a [[coal phase-out]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sartor |first1=O. |title=Implementing coal transitions Insights from case studies of major coal-consuming economies |date=2018 |publisher=IDDRI and Climate Strategies. |url=https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/coal_synthesis_final.pdf |access-date=2018-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025225556/https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/coal_synthesis_final.pdf |archive-date=2018-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> \u2013 an area for planned cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey, Germany agree to join forces for new energy, industry projects |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/27/turkey-germany-agree-to-join-forces-for-new-energy-industry-projects |work=Daily Sabah |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027003225/https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/27/turkey-germany-agree-to-join-forces-for-new-energy-industry-projects |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In terms of energy resources, Spain is more similar, having hydropower and abundant sunshine, and its transition away from coal could also be a model.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain to close most coalmines in \u20ac250m transition deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/oct/26/spain-to-close-most-coal-mines-after-striking-250m-deal |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027061514/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/oct/26/spain-to-close-most-coal-mines-after-striking-250m-deal |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkish industry has experience converting coal to solar outside the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefifthestate.com.au/energy-lead/energy/eastern-europe-shows-how-to-convert-coal-to-solar/|title=Eastern Europe shows how to convert coal to solar|date=2020-03-03|website=The Fifth Estate|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[OECD]] said that Turkey's coal-fired power plant development programme is creating a high [[carbon lock-in]] risk due to the large [[capital cost]]s and long infrastructure lifetimes.<ref>OECD (2019), p. 40</ref> It also stated that energy and climate policies that are not aligned in future may prevent some assets from providing an economic return due to the transition to a [[low-carbon economy]].<ref>OECD (2019), p. 39</ref> Additionally, new wind or solar power is forecast to be cheaper than new coal-fired power plants by 2022 by the think tank [[Carbon Tracker]]. The average Turkish coal-fired power station is predicted to have higher long-run operating costs than new renewables by 2023<ref name=Carbtrkfullrep2018>{{cite web |title=Powering down coal: Navigating the economic and financial risks in the last years of coal power |url=https://www.carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/CTI_Powering_Down_Coal_Report_Nov_2018-1.pdf |publisher=[[Carbon Tracker Initiative]] |date=November 2018 |access-date=2018-12-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223121215/https://www.carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/CTI_Powering_Down_Coal_Report_Nov_2018-1.pdf |archive-date=2018-12-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> and all renewables by 2030.<ref name=\"Carbtrk2018\">{{cite web |title=Powering down coal: Navigating the economic and financial risks in the last years of coal power |url=https://www.carbontracker.org/reports/coal-portal/ |publisher=[[Carbon Tracker Initiative]] |accessdate=30 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005020/https://www.carbontracker.org/reports/coal-portal/ |archive-date=1 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> As lignite power plants tend to be inland replacing them with solar or wind power could save water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.triplepundit.com/story/2019/wind-could-power-30-percent-global-electricity-production-2050/85796/|title=Wind Could Provide 30 Percent of Global Electricity By 2050|website=www.triplepundit.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215090204/https://www.triplepundit.com/story/2019/wind-could-power-30-percent-global-electricity-production-2050/85796/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Employment===\nBy the end of 2017, the renewable energy industry employed 84,000 people,<ref>{{cite web |title=How Turkey Can Ensure a Successful Energy Transition |url=https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/security/reports/2018/07/10/453281/turkey-can-ensure-successful-energy-transition/ |publisher=Center for American Progress |accessdate=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063254/https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/security/reports/2018/07/10/453281/turkey-can-ensure-successful-energy-transition/ |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> whereas coal mining employed 10,000 in 13 public-sector workplaces and 26,000 in 430 private-sector workplaces.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maden \u0130statistikleri |url=http://mapeg.gov.tr/maden_istatistik.aspx |publisher=MAPEG |accessdate=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222204844/http://mapeg.gov.tr/maden_istatistik.aspx |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, the minimum wage for coal miners was 4,059 lira (US$700) per month, twice the standard minimum wage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Changes to minimum wage, severance payments and administrative fines |url=https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Employment-Benefits/Turkey/Gn-Partners/Changes-to-minimum-wage-severance-payments-and-administrative-fines |publisher=G\u00fcn and Partners |accessdate=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213080534/https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Employment-Benefits/Turkey/Gn-Partners/Changes-to-minimum-wage-severance-payments-and-administrative-fines |archive-date=13 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nDue to the complex geology of the [[Zonguldak basin]], hardcoal production in Turkey is insignificant, heavily subsidised and labour-intensive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey: country profile |url=https://euracoal.eu/info/country-profiles/turkey/ |publisher=Euracoal |accessdate=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027232015/https://euracoal.eu/info/country-profiles/turkey/ |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, [[Zonguldak Province]] is highly dependent on coal:<ref>{{cite book |last1=ERGEN |first1=Mustafa |title=A New Methodology Proposal for Urban Regeneration of Brownfield Areas; Case Study of Zonguldak City, Turkey|date=7 March 2013 |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/46912647.pdf |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027190701/https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/46912647.pdf |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, most working men in [[Zonguldak]] city were employed in the coal industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2018/10/05/absolute-darkness-a-day-in-a-miners-life|title=Absolute darkness: A day in a miner's life|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720135706/https://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2018/10/05/absolute-darkness-a-day-in-a-miners-life|archive-date=2019-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, {{As of|2020||lc=y}}, Turkey had not implemented a [[Just Transition|just transition]] policy, although the government spoke in favor of it in 2015.<ref name=\"ClimateTransparency2019\" /> Three coal-fired power plants, which are in [[Mu\u011fla Province]], [[Yata\u011fan power station|Yata\u011fan]], Yenik\u00f6y and Kemerk\u00f6y, are becoming outdated. Currently, the old plants need refurbishment to meet forthcoming local air pollution limits. [[Climate Action Network]] Europe recommends shutting them down instead of refurbishing them if the subsidies are redeployed locally as the most economically feasible option. However, if the plants and associated lignite mines were shut down, about 5000 workers would need funding for early retirement or retraining.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Real Costs of Coal: Mu\u011fla|url=http://costsofcoal.caneurope.org/ |publisher=[[Climate Action Network]] Europe |accessdate=25 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126001032/http://costsofcoal.caneurope.org/ |archive-date=26 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There would also be health and environmental benefits, but these are difficult to quantify as very little official data is released on the local pollution by the plants and mines.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Turkey|Global Warming}}\n\n* {{annotated link|Environmental issues in Turkey}}\n* {{annotated link|Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey}}\n* {{annotated link|Glossary of coal mining terminology}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite report  \n |work=[[Turkish Statistical Institute]]\n |title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory report [TurkStat report]\n |date=April 2020\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/tur-2020-nir-13apr20.zip\n }}\n\n*{{cite web  \n |work=[[Turkish Statistical Institute]]\n |title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory 1990 - 2018 common reporting format (CRF) tables [TurkStat tables]\n |date=April 2020\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/tur-2020-crf-13apr20.zip\n |format=TUR_2020_2018_13042020_112534.xlsx\n }}\n\n*{{cite report  \n |work=[[UNFCCC]]\n |title=Report on the individual review of the inventory submission of Turkey submitted in 2018\n |date=May 2019\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/ARR2018_TUR.pdf\n }}\n\n*{{cite report  \n |work=[[OECD]]\n |title=OECD Environmental Performance Reviews: Turkey 2019\n |date=February 2019\n |doi=10.1787/9789264309753-en\n |series=OECD Environmental Performance Reviews\n |isbn=9789264309760\n }}\n\n*{{cite report  \n |work=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|MENR]] Elec.\n |title=Investor's Guide for Electricity sector in Turkey \n |date=September 2019\n|url=https://www.enerji.gov.tr/File/?path=ROOT%252f1%252fDocuments%252fAnnouncement%252fInvestor%25e2%2580%2599s%2bGuide%2bfor%2bElectricity%2bSector%2bin%2bTurkey%2b.pdf&version1%2c00\n }}\n\n*{{cite report \n |work=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|MENR]] Mine\n |title=Investor's Guide for Mining sector in Turkey \n |date=September 2019\n |url=https://www.enerji.gov.tr/File/?path=ROOT%252f1%252fDocuments%252fAnnouncement%252fInvestor%25e2%2580%2599s%2bGuide%2bfor%2bMining%2bSector%2bin%2bTurkey%2b.pdf&version1%2c00\n }}\n\n*{{cite report\n |last1=Doukas\n |first1=Alex\n |last2=Gen\u00e7s\u00fc\n |first2=Ipek\n |date=June 2019 \n |title=Turkey: G20 coal subsidies\n |work=[[Overseas Development Institute]]\n|url=https://www.odi.org/sites/odi.org.uk/files/resource-documents/12752.pdf \n }}\n\n*{{cite report\n |last=Jensen\n |first=Genon K.\n |title=Lignite coal \u2013 health effects and recommendations from the health sector\n |url=https://www.env-health.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/HEAL-Lignite-Briefing-en_web.pdf\n |publisher=Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL)\n |date = December 2018}}\n\n*{{cite report\n | author      = \u00c7\u0131nar Engineering Consultancy \n | year        = 2019\n | title       = Af\u015fin C power station environmental impact report\n | lang        = tr\n | url         = http://eced.csb.gov.tr/ced/jsp/ek1/23019#\n | publisher   = [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)]]\n}}\n\n*{{cite report\n | author      = M\u00fccella Ersoy, R&D and Foreign Affairs Manager, TKI \n | year        = 2019\n | title       = Turkish coal mining sector: Current State, Strategy for the Future\n | url         = http://www.unece.org/fileadmin/DAM/energy/images/CMM/CMM_CE/Turkey_2019/3._2019-_CBM_Workshop-M_Ersoy-100619.pdf\n | publisher   = [[Turkish Coal Operations Authority]]\n}}\n\n*{{cite report\n |date         = January 2020 \n |title        = E\u00dcA\u015e - A briefing for investors, insurers and banks\n |publisher    = [[Beyond Coal|Europe Beyond Coal]]\n |url          = https://beyond-coal.eu/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/EBC_EUAS_briefing-paper.pdf\n}}\n\n*{{cite web \n |title        = National Energy Balance tables annually since 1972\n |publisher    = Energy Administration (part of the [[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources]])\n |url          = https://www.eigm.gov.tr/tr-TR/Denge-Tablolari/Denge-Tablolari\n |language         = tr\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.turkiye.gov.tr/migem-e-maden E-maden (government repository of mining information - in Turkish and access restricted)] \n* [https://www.env-health.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/HEAL-Lignite-Briefing-en_web.pdf Lignite coal \u2013 health effects and recommendations from the health sector]\n* [http://www.komurder.org/ K\u00f6m\u00fcr \u00dcreticileri Derne\u011fi (Turkish Coal Producers Association)]\n* [https://www.shura.org.tr/eng/ SHURA Energy Transition Center]\n* [https://seffaflik.epias.com.tr/transparency/index.xhtml Electricity markets, generation and consumption up to date statistics]\n* [https://www.electricitymap.org/?page=country&solar=false&remote=true&wind=false&countryCode=TR Live carbon emissions from electricity generation]\n* [https://www.gem.wiki/Alternatives_to_coal_in_Turkey \"Alternatives to coal in Turkey\" article [[Global Energy Monitor]]]\n* [https://beyond-coal.eu/category/country/turkey/ Beyond Coal articles [[Beyond Coal]]]\n\n{{Asia topic|Coal in}}\n{{Europe topic|Coal in}}\n\n[[Category:Coal in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Climate change in Turkey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use European English|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Coal mining, power, industry, and its health and environmental problems in the Eurasian country}}\n[[File:TKI Dragline.JPG|thumb|State-owned lignite company [[Turkish Coal Operations Authority]] dragline in Yenik\u00f6y, [[Milas]]]]\n\n[[Coal]] supplied over a quarter of [[Energy in Turkey|Turkey's primary energy]] from the 1990s to the 2010s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea.org/countries/turkey|title=Total primary energy supply (TPES) by source, Turkey|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The heavily [[energy subsidies#Turkey|subsidised]] coal industry generates over a third of the [[Electricity sector in Turkey|country's electricity]]<ref name=\"MinEn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal|title=Coal|publisher=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917110843/http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal|archive-date=17 September 2018|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> and emits a third of  [[greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey|Turkey's greenhouse gases]]. Every year, thousands of people die prematurely from coal-related causes, the most common of which is [[Air pollution in Turkey|local air pollution]].\n\nMost coal mined in Turkey is [[lignite]] (brown coal), which is more polluting than other types of coal.<ref name=HEAL2018>{{cite web |title=Lignite coal \u2013 health effects and recommendations from the health sector |url=https://www.env-health.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/HEAL-Lignite-Briefing-en_web.pdf |publisher=Health and Environment Alliance (HEAL) |date=December 2018 |access-date=2019-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211010345/https://www.env-health.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/HEAL-Lignite-Briefing-en_web.pdf |archive-date=2018-12-11 |url-status=live }}</ref>  [[Energy policy of Turkey|Turkey's energy policy]] encourages mining lignite for [[List of coal-fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations]] in order to reduce [[Energy in Turkey#Gas|gas imports]];<ref name=\"MinEn\" /> and coal supplies over 40% of domestic energy production.<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 5</ref> Mining peaked in 2018, at over 100 million tonnes,<ref name=\"AA1\">{{cite news |title=Turkey breaks local coal production record in 2018 |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-breaks-local-coal-production-record-in-2018/1366302 |agency=Anadolu Agency |date=16 January 2019 |access-date=2 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203085042/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/economy/turkey-breaks-local-coal-production-record-in-2018/1366302 |archive-date=3 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and declined considerably in 2019.<ref name=\":0\" /> Almost all local coal is lignite, whereas Turkey imports almost all of the [[bituminous coal]] it uses. The largest coalfield in Turkey is [[Elbistan coalfield|Elbistan]].<ref name=\"HDN1\">{{cite news |title=Turkey transfers operating rights of seven coal fields to private companies |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-transfers-operating-rights-of-seven-coal-fields-to-private-companies-137794 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=12 October 2018 |access-date=12 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012103505/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-transfers-operating-rights-of-seven-coal-fields-to-private-companies-137794 |archive-date=12 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Zonguldak TTK liman\u0131.jpg|thumb|Wharf that formerly shipped coal out of Zonguldak]]\n[[File:Ottoman submarine Abdulhamid 1886.jpg|thumb|Coal-fired [[Ottoman submarine Abd\u00fcl Hamid]], built in 1886]]\nAs the [[List of major surface ships of the Ottoman steam navy|Ottoman Navy expanded its steam powered fleet]] in the 1840s it was important to find domestic coalfields, to help defend the [[Ottoman Empire]] against the expanding [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\":3\" /> There are several stories, probably untrue, about the discovery of coal on the [[Black Sea]] coast in what is now  [[Zonguldak Province]]: but historians know that the Ere\u011fli Coal Mine Company started production in 1842 and that coal mined in [[Karadeniz Ere\u011fli|Ere\u011fli]] and [[Amasra]] was used to fuel steamboats.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Ayhan |first1=Arda |title=The History of Coal in Turkey and the Story of its Origins |url=http://www.miningturkeymag.com/pdfler/mak-1466845656.pdf |accessdate=30 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005026/http://www.miningturkeymag.com/pdfler/mak-1466845656.pdf |archive-date=1 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1848 the Ere\u011fli Coal Basin (now called the [[Zonguldak basin|Zonguldak Basin]]) was mapped and claimed by [[Abdulmejid I|Sultan Abdulmejid I]], who later leased it, mainly to foreign merchants.<ref name=\":3\" /> The first customer of Turkey's coal industry was the [[Ottoman Navy]], but for the [[Crimean War]] in the mid-1850s production was commandeered by their allies, the [[Royal Navy#1815\u20131914|British Royal Navy]],<ref name=\":3\" /> and production increased by importing mining machinery and training Turkish miners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dergipark.org.tr/en/download/article-file/44295|title=Underground mining operations in Zonguldak coal mines|last=G\u00fcney|first=Mehmet|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> By 1875 the Ottoman Navy had become the third largest in the world and expansion of the mines attracted workers from outside the area, despite the dangerous conditions.<ref>{{Citation|last=\u015eeng\u00fcl|first=H. Tar\u0131k|title=Zonguldak Coalfield and the Past and Future of Turkish Coal-mining Communities|date=2012|work=Changing Work and Community Identities in European Regions: Perspectives on the Past and Present|pages=154\u2013183|editor-last=Kirk|editor-first=John|series=Identity Studies in the Social Sciences|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|language=en|doi=10.1057/9780230353916_6|isbn=9780230353916|last2=Aytekin|first2=E. Attila|editor2-last=Contrepois|editor2-first=Sylvie|editor3-last=Jefferys|editor3-first=Steve}}</ref>\n \nThe first power station [[Silahtara\u011fa Power Station]] (now  [[SantralIstanbul]] culture center) opened in 1914, and after the defeat of the empire in [[World War I]], and the subsequent [[Turkish War of Independence]], the new Republic of Turkey [[Atat\u00fcrk's Reforms#Industry|industrialized further as part of Atat\u00fcrk's reforms]]. Lignite from Soma supplied the army in WW1<ref name=\":3\" /> and lignite mining began at several other coalfields in 1927.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Atalay|first=Figen|date=2015|title=The History of the Coal Mining Industry and Mining Accidents in the World and Turkey|journal=Turkish Thoracic Journal|volume=16|issue=Suppl 1|pages=S5\u2013S8|doi=10.5152/ttd.2015.002|issn=2148-7197|pmc=5783104|pmid=29404107}}</ref> But Zonguldak remains the only national source of the hard coal which was necessary for steelmaking: its mines were [[nationalization|nationalized]] in 1940.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesis.bilkent.edu.tr/0001720.pdf|title=Workers of the Ere\u011fli\u0307-Zonguldak Coal Basin, 1848-1922|last=Aytekin|first=Erden Attila|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In the mid-20th century the state encouraged the growth of [[cement]]<ref name=\":3\" /> and steelmaking in Zonguldak; and in the late 20th century many power stations were constructed near lignite fields such as [[Elbistan coalfield]].\n\nIn the early 21st century there was a growing realisation of coal's damage to health, but the state wished to avoid importing too much natural gas, which was expensive at that time: the nascent environmental movement was unable to prevent many more coal-fired power stations being built. After years of struggle by environmentalists flue emissions standards were finally improved at the end of the 2010s, resulting in the closure of a few older plants. As for [[steelmaking]], most plants are now [[electric arc furnace]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cib.org.tr/en/statistics.html|title=STATISTICS|website=Turkish Steel|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Coalfields and mines==\n{{See also|Category:Coal mines in Turkey}}\nDue to the country's geology, coal mines must reach very deep to obtain coal of decent quality.<ref name=GBR/> In 2017 almost half of the coal was mined by the state but the government wishes to privatize more.<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 8</ref> As of 2019, there are 436 [[coal mining]] companies,<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 3</ref> 740 coal mines,<ref>{{cite news |title=Coal mine collapses in Turkey |url=https://en.trend.az/world/turkey/3021127.html |agency=Trend |date=18 February 2019 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301013429/https://en.trend.az/world/turkey/3021127.html |archive-date=1 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and more mining and exploration licences are being tendered.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tender announcements |url=http://mapeg.gov.tr/Ihaleler.aspx |publisher=MAPEG |accessdate=24 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190225044828/http://mapeg.gov.tr/Ihaleler.aspx |archive-date=25 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, some drilling companies are not bidding for licences because mineral exploration is more profitable.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=38 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018 many mining licences were combined.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=37 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mining is documented in the \"e-maden\" computer system (\"maden\" means \"mine\" in Turkish).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjiportali.com/mapeg-bazi-islemleri-sadece-e-maden-portali-uzerinden-kabul-edecek/|title=MAPEG, Baz\u0131 \u0130\u015flemleri Sadece E-Maden Portal\u0131 \u00dczerinden Kabul Edecek!|date=2019-12-12|website=Enerji Portal\u0131|language=tr|access-date=2020-01-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128085419/https://www.enerjiportali.com/mapeg-bazi-islemleri-sadece-e-maden-portali-uzerinden-kabul-edecek/|archive-date=2020-01-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Coal miners do not have the right to [[Strike action|strike]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tr.usembassy.gov/2019-country-reports-on-human-rights-practices-turkey/|title=2019 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices: Turkey|date=2020-03-12|website=U.S. Embassy & Consulates in Turkey|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Hard coal===\nThe [[Zonguldak basin]] in the northwest is the only coal mining region in Turkey that produces hard coal:{{refn|group=note|[[Bituminous coal]] is called hardcoal (ta\u015fk\u00f6m\u00fcr in Turkish) in the [[International Energy Agency]] document for Turkey and anthracite in Turkish government documents. On Wikipedia, ''hardcoal'' redirects to [[anthracite]].}} about 2 million tons a year<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/enerji-piyasalarinda-2020-yili-ongoruleri-31771yy.htm|title=Enerji piyasalar\u0131nda 2020 y\u0131l\u0131 \u00f6ng\u00f6r\u00fcleri|last=Di\u0307reskeneli\u0307|first=Haluk|date=2020-01-03|website=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref> from mines including [[Armut\u00e7uk coal mine|Kandilli]], [[Amasra]], [[Karadon coal mine|Karadon]], [[Kozlu coal mine|Kozlu]] and [[\u00dcz\u00fclmez coal mine|\u00dcz\u00fclmez]].<ref name=Mills2014/> Compared to other countries, the [[Energy value of coal|energy value of the coal]] is low, at {{convert|4,000|kcal/kg|kcal/lb}} to {{convert|6,000|kcal/kg|kcal/lb|abbr=on}}. Although low grade it is generally [[Coke (fuel)|cokeable]] or semi-cokeable quality.<ref name=Esmaeili2018>{{cite web |title=Carbon Capture, Utilization and Storage in the Context of Turkish Energy Market |url=https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |publisher=IICEC |date=June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181030/https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Mills2014>{{cite web |title=Prospects for coal and clean coal technologies in Turkey |url=https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |publisher=IEACCC |date=July 2014 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181742/https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Long-wall mining]] is necessary due to the tectonic structure of the seams.<ref name=GBR/>\n\n===Lignite===\nThe  most significant deposits are [[Neogene]] period,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Coal Deposits of Turkey: Properties and Importance on Energy Demand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259563494_Coal_deposits_of_Turkey_properties_and_importance_on_energy_demand|journal=Bulletin of the Geological Society of Greece|volume=|pages=}}</ref> and in 2018 Turkey was the third-largest lignite mining country,<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 7</ref> with 7% of world production.<ref name=HEAL2018/> Almost half of the country's lignite reserves are in the [[Elbistan coalfield|Af\u015fin\u2013Elbistan basin]].<ref name=\"MinEn\" /> Lignite coalfields include [[Elbistan coalfield|Elbistan]], Kutahya Tavsanl\u0131, Inez, [[Manisa]], \u0130na\u011fz\u0131-Ba\u011fl\u0131k and [[Gediz, K\u00fctahya|Gediz]].<ref name=\"SPG2018\">{{cite news |title=Turkish government to transfer 203 million mt of coal reserves to private owners |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/101218-turkish-government-to-transfer-203-million-mt-of-coal-reserves-to-private-owners |publisher=S & P Global |date=12 Oct 2018 |access-date=16 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016165428/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/101218-turkish-government-to-transfer-203-million-mt-of-coal-reserves-to-private-owners |archive-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Mills2014/>  Locations of major individual lignite mines include [[Tun\u00e7bilek power station|Tun\u00e7bilek]] in [[Tav\u015fanl\u0131]], [[Yata\u011fan, Mu\u011fla|Yata\u011fan]] near the southern [[Aegean Sea]], [[Yenik\u00f6y power station|Yenik\u00f6y]] in [[Mu\u011fla Province|Mu\u011fla]] and [[Seyit\u00f6mer power station|Seyit\u00f6mer]] in [[K\u00fctahya]]; and there is a [[gilsonite]] mine in [[Silopi]].<ref name=Mills2014/> Turkish lignite has high carbon,{{refn|group=note|The [[Heat of combustion#Lower heating value|net calorific value]] of Turkish lignite is lower than that of typical lignite,<ref>Turkstat report (2020), p. 50</ref> varying by power station; its average is about 2,800|kcal/kg.<ref name=SETA2019>{{cite web |title=Yerli\u0307 ve mi\u0307lli\u0307 enerji\u0307 poli\u0307ti\u0307kalari ekseni\u0307nde k\u00f6m\u00fcr |url=https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |publisher=SETAV |accessdate=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214061430/https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The average carbon content of lignite in Turkey is higher than that of typical lignite, measured at 30.5 kg/GJ in 2018.<ref>Turkstat report (2020), p. 50</ref>}} sulphur, ash, moisture and volatile components.\n<ref name=Esmaeili2018>{{cite web |title=Carbon Capture, Utilization and Storage in the Context of Turkish Energy Market |url=https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |publisher=IICEC |date=June 2018 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181030/https://iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/sites/iicec.sabanciuniv.edu/files/1806%20IICECE%26CPaperCCUSinTurkey_0.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Mills2014>{{cite web |title=Prospects for coal and clean coal technologies in Turkey |url=https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |publisher=IEACCC |date=July 2014 |access-date=2019-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107181742/https://www.usea.org/sites/default/files/072014_Prospects%20for%20coal%20and%20clean%20coal%20technologies%20in%20Turkey_ccc239.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Mining Technology===\nExploration and research is done by Maden Tetkik Arama Genel M\u00fcd\u00fcrl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc (MTA).<ref name=\":2\" />  In the 2010s coal mining technology from China was imported.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=35 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> But according to energy analyst Haluk Direskeneli coal power plant technology which has been imported is unsuitable for Turkish coal, so [[refractory]] distortions are occurring, and [[control system]]s and other equipment is failing. He says that [[circulating fluidized bed]] (CFB) technology is unsuitable because Turkish lignite does not burn continuously in the CFB combustion chamber without supplementary liquid fuel. In Direskeneli's opinion \"local coal enters the combustion chamber as ice in winter and as mud in summer\", so the water content of domestic coal should be reduced by preheating.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurasiareview.com/02122019-turkey-energy-and-infrastructure-forecast-2020-oped/|title=Turkey: Energy And Infrastructure Forecast 2020 \u2013 OpEd|last=Direskeneli|first=Haluk|date=2019-12-02|website=Eurasia Review|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204173245/https://www.eurasiareview.com/02122019-turkey-energy-and-infrastructure-forecast-2020-oped/|archive-date=2019-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, environmental regulations for coal mines still lag behind international standards despite improvements.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=33|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|2019}} an expansion of coal washing capacity was planned together with research on [[coal pollution mitigation]] and lignite [[gasification]].<ref>Ersoy (2019), p. 15</ref>\n\n==Health and safety==\n\nThe Istanbul Policy Center estimates that, every year, coal causes at least 2,800 premature deaths, 637,000 working days to be lost, and 3.6 billion euros in additional costs. Although there are some concerns about ground{{refn|group=note|[[Fly ash]], a byproduct of the coal refining process, is often sold to cement factories as a raw material.<ref name=HEAL2018/> Concentrations of natural [[radionuclides]] vary depending on the power station and the product may be safe in building materials depending on the amount used.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ozden |first1=Banu |last2=G\u00fcler |first2=Erkan |last3=Vaasma |first3=Taavi |last4=Horv\u00e1th |first4=M\u00e1ria |last5=Kiisk |first5=Madis |last6=Kov\u00e1cs |first6=Tibor |title=Enrichment of naturally occurring radionuclides and trace elements in Yatagan and Yenikoy coal-fired thermal power plants, Turkey |journal=Journal of Environmental Radioactivity |date=August 2018 |volume=188 |pages=100\u2013107 |doi=10.1016/j.jenvrad.2017.09.016 |pmid=28965987 }}</ref>}} and water<ref>{{Cite journal|last=U\u00e7ar|first=Ali|last2=\u015eens\u00f6\u011f\u00fct|first2=Cem|last3=Ediz|first3=\u0130 G\u00f6ktay|date=2019-01-05|title=Invest\u0131gat\u0131on for Env\u0131ronmental Effects and Evaluat\u0131on of F\u0131ne Ta\u0131l\u0131ngs from Tuncb\u0131lek Coal Process\u0131ng Plant/Turkey|url=http://econ-environ-geol.org/index.php/ojs/article/view/12|journal=International Journal of Economic and Environmental Geology|language=en|pages=28\u201334|issn=2223-957X}}</ref> pollution; [[particulates]], which are microscopic airborne particles, cause most coal-related deaths by worsening [[air pollution in Turkey]].<ref name=HEAL2018/>\n\n===Workers' health and safety===\nAfter the deaths of over 300 people in the [[Soma mine disaster]] in 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/turkey/turkey-rights-violations-found-in-mine-disaster-case/1759720|title=Turkey: Rights violations found in mine disaster case|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> new health and safety regulations were introduced. {{As of|2018}}, most mining accidents happen in coal mines but the reasons for Turkey's poor mining safety are not entirely clear.<ref>{{cite book |title=Turkey Mining 2018 |publisher=Global Business Reports |pages=14\u201315 |url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |access-date=2019-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf |archive-date=2019-05-17 |url-status=live }}</ref> The government has restricted access to workplace accident statistics, but coal mining is thought to be the most accident-prone sector of the economy.<ref name=HEAL2018/> {{As of|2018|}} coal mining fatalities continue to occur in [[Illegal mining|illegal mines]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Two workers killed in illegal mine collapse in Turkey's Zonguldak |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/two-workers-killed-in-illegal-mine-collapse-in-turkeys-zonguldak-134293 |agency=H\u00fcrriyet |date=8 July 2018 |access-date=31 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231194036/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/two-workers-killed-in-illegal-mine-collapse-in-turkeys-zonguldak-134293 |archive-date=31 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Coal miners suffer respiratory diseases such as [[Coalworker's pneumoconiosis|black lung]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ghs.asyod.org/Konular/2019-2-19.pdf|title=Coal Worker's Pneumoconiosis|last=ERBOY|first=Fatma|date=|website=|publisher=Zonguldak Kara Elmas \u00dcniversitesi T\u0131p Fak\u00fcltesi, G\u00f6\u011f\u00fcs Hastal\u0131klar\u0131 Ana Bilim Dal\u0131, Zonguldak|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127152227/http://ghs.asyod.org/Konular/2019-2-19.pdf|archive-date=2020-01-27|access-date=}}</ref>, [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]],<ref name=\":4\" /> [[back pain]],<ref>{{cite journal |title=Low back pain and lumbar angles in Turkish coal miners |journal=American Journal of Industrial Medicine |volume=50 |issue=2 |pages=92\u201396 |doi=10.1002/ajim.20417 |pmid=17238134 |url=https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/biblio/20885715 |year=2007 |last1=Sarikaya |first1=Selda |last2=\u00d6zdolap |first2=\u015eenay |last3=G\u00fcm\u00fc\u015ftas\u015f |first3=\u015eenol |last4=Ko\u00e7 |first4=\u00dclk\u00fc |access-date=2018-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027185620/https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/biblio/20885715 |archive-date=2018-10-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[periodontal disease]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=\u0130nan\u00e7 Cengiz |first1=Murat |last2=Zengin |first2=B\u00fc\u015fra |last3=\u0130\u00e7en |first3=Murat |last4=K\u00f6kt\u00fcrk |first4=Fir\u00fczan |title=Prevalence of periodontal disease among mine workers of Zonguldak, Kozlu District, Turkey: a cross-sectional study |journal=BMC Public Health |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=361 |date=2018 |doi=10.1186/s12889-018-5304-1 |pmid=29548308 |pmc=5857090 }}</ref> and other illnesses; and increased risk from [[respiratory infections]] such as [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/04/turkey-coronavirus-coal-mines-pollution-dirty-air-zonguldak.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak exposes health risks of coal rush|last=Ugurtas|first=Selin|date=2020-04-17|website=Al-Monitor|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> \n\n===Air pollution===\n[[File:Yenik\u00f6y Power Plant Milas Mu\u011fla Turkey.jpg|thumb|[[Yenik\u00f6y power station]] in [[Milas]], [[Mu\u011fla Province|Mu\u011fla]]]]\n{{See also|Air pollution in Turkey}}\nAir pollution from some large coal-fired power stations is publicly visible in [[Sentinel-5 Precursor|Sentinel satellite]] data.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polluters exposed by new eye in the sky satellite |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-44705268 |date=5 July 2018 |access-date=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152552/https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-44705268 |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TROPOMI Level 2 data products |url=http://www.tropomi.eu/data-products/level-2-products |publisher=KNMI R&D Satellite Observations |accessdate=24 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152638/http://www.tropomi.eu/data-products/level-2-products |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) says that old coal-fired power stations and residential heating are emitting dangerous levels of fine particulates: so it recommends reducing particulate emissions by replacing coal used for residential heating with gas, and retrofitting or closing old coal-fired power plants.<ref>OECD (2019), p. 20</ref> Although the Turkish government receives reports of measurements of air pollution from the smokestacks of individual coal-fired power stations, it does not publish the reports, unlike the EU. The OECD has also recommended Turkey create and publish a [[pollutant release and transfer register]].<ref>OECD (2019), p. 30</ref>\n\nFlue gas emission limits in milligrams per cubic metre (mg/Nm<sup>3</sup>) are:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iea-coal.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Turkey-emissions-standard.pdf|title=Emission standards: Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=[[International Energy Agency]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Sanayi\u0307 Kaynakli Hava Ki\u0307rli\u0307li\u0307\u011fi\u0307ni\u0307n Kontrol\u00fc Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307\u011fi\u0307nde De\u011fi\u0307\u015fi\u0307kli\u0307k Yapilmasina Dai\u0307r Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307k |journal=Resm\u00ee Gazete |date=20 December 2014 |issue=29211 |page=Appx 1 page 15 |url=http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2014/12/20141220-2.htm |access-date=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227034715/http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2014/12/20141220-2.htm |archive-date=27 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Size of power station     !! Dust !! [[Sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]] !! [[Nitrogen dioxide|NO<sub>2</sub>]] !! [[Carbon monoxide|CO]]\n|-\n| 0.5 MW \u2264 capacity < 5 MW  || 200  || see cited source                  ||  see cited source                   || 200\n|-\n| 5 MW \u2264 capacity   < 50 MW || 150  || see cited source                  ||  see cited source                   || 200\n|-\n| 50 MW \u2264 capacity < 100 MW ||  50  ||                               850 || 400                                 || 150\n|-\n| capacity         \u2265 100 MW ||  30  ||                               200 || 200                                 || 200\n|-\n|}\n\n(see cited source for more details, such as some SO<sub>2</sub> exceptions) and some plants lack [[electrostatic precipitator]] filters.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Environment Minister]] Murat Kurum said in December 2019 that unless plants which emit over the limits start installing the necessary filters during the first half of 2020 they will face fines, nationalization or closure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-dunya-50653983|title=Erdo\u011fan'\u0131n veto karar\u0131n\u0131n alt\u0131nda ne yat\u0131yor?|last=Say\u0131n|first=Ay\u015fe|date=2019-12-04|work=[[BBC]]|access-date=2019-12-05|language=tr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191205034739/https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-dunya-50653983|archive-date=2019-12-05|url-status=live}}</ref> The limits are laxer than the EU [[Industrial Emissions Directive]] and the [[Sulfur dioxide|SO<sub>2</sub>]] limit for large coal-fired power plants in other countries, such as India at 100&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup>, and China at 35&nbsp;mg/m<sup>3</sup>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenpeace.org/international/press-release/23819/global-so2-air-pollution-hotspots-ranked-by-greenpeace-analysis|title=Greenpeace analysis ranks global SO2 air pollution hotspots|website=Greenpeace International|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901063929/https://www.greenpeace.org/international/press-release/23819/global-so2-air-pollution-hotspots-ranked-by-greenpeace-analysis/|archive-date=2019-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018}}, air pollution in districts that are near coal-fired power stations greatly exceeds national limits of PM10 (coarse particulate matter) and SO<sub>2</sub>. In [[Elbistan]] district, PM10 averages are over three times the regulatory limit, and in [[Soma, Manisa|Soma]] SO<sub>2</sub> averages are over four times the limit.<ref>{{cite book |title=Hava Kirlili\u011fi ve Sa\u011fl\u0131k Etkileri Kara Rapor |date=11 May 2019 |pages=52\u201353 |url=https://www.temizhavahakki.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Hava-Kirlilig%CC%86i-ve-Sag%CC%86l%C4%B1k-Etkileri-Kara-Rapor-2019.pdf |access-date=11 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606182418/https://www.temizhavahakki.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Hava-Kirlili%C4%9Fi-ve-Sa%C4%9Fl%C4%B1k-Etkileri-Kara-Rapor-2019.pdf |archive-date=6 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2019}}, according to [[Greenpeace]] air pollution around power plants in [[K\u00fctahya Province]] was three times higher than [[World Health Organisation]] recommended limits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ahvalnews.com/environment/turkish-minister-says-coal-plants-must-start-using-pollution-filters-6-months|title=Turkish minister says coal plants must start using pollution filters in 6 months|website=Ahval|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191204062736/https://ahvalnews.com/environment/turkish-minister-says-coal-plants-must-start-using-pollution-filters-6-months|archive-date=2019-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\n\n===Greenhouse gas emissions===\n{{See also|Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey#Coal}}\n[[File:Fossil fuel CO2 Turkey.svg|thumb|CO2 from burning fossil fuels]]\n[[File:Ghg pie chart Turkey 2018.svg|thumb|Greenhouse gas emissions in 2018]]\nCoal combustion emitted over 150{{Spaces}}Mt of [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] in total in 2018,{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2020|p=57}} about a third of Turkey's greenhouse gas.{{efn|1=29% of the 521 Mt gross emissions in 2018 or 35% of the 426 Mt net emissions}} Emissions from individual power plants over 20 MW are measured.<ref>{{Cite web|title=ETS Detailed Information: Turkey|url=https://icapcarbonaction.com/en/?option=com_etsmap&task=export&format=pdf&layout=list&systems%5B%5D=66|website=International Carbon Action Partnership|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[life-cycle greenhouse-gas emissions of energy sources|Life-cycle emissions]] of Turkish coal-fired power stations are over 1 kg [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2</sub>eq]] per kilowatt-hour.<ref name=\"Atilgan\">{{cite journal |last1=Atilgan |first1=Burcin |last2=Azapagic |first2=Adisa |title=An integrated life cycle sustainability assessment of electricity generation in Turkey |journal=Energy Policy |date=2016 |volume=93 |page=177|doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2016.02.055 |doi-access=free }}</ref> The [[environmental impact assessment]] (EIA) for the proposed [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station]] [[Fossil fuel power station#Estimation of carbon dioxide emissions|estimated {{CO2}} emissions]] would be more than 60&nbsp;million tonnes of {{CO2}} per year.{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=319|quote = Atmosfere Verilecek CO2 Miktar\u0131: ....... = 61.636.279,98 tCO2/y\u0131l\" means \"Amount of CO2 which will be emitted to the atmosphere: ....... = 61,636,279.98 tCO2/year\"}} By comparison, total annual [[greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey]] are about 520&nbsp;million tonnes;<ref name=\"Anadolu1\">{{cite news|quote = Turkey's total greenhouse gas emissions in 2018 ..... equivalent to 520.9 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2). |publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/life/environment/turkeys-greenhouse-gas-emissions-fall-for-second-year-in-a-row|title=Turkey's greenhouse gas emissions fall for second year in a row|date=2020-03-31|work=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> thus more than a tenth of greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey would be from the planned power station.{{refn|group=note|62 megatonnes would be emitted annually{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=319|quote = Atmosfere Verilecek CO2 Miktar\u0131: ....... = 61.636.279,98 tCO2/y\u0131l\" means \"Amount of CO2 which will be emitted to the atmosphere: ....... = 61,636,279.98 tCO2/year\"}} if run at the targeted [[capacity factor]], whereas Turkey's current annual emissions are 521 megatonnes.<ref name=\"Anadolu1\"/> [[Wikipedia:No original research#Routine calculations|By simple arithmetic]] 62 megatonnes is more than 10% of 521+62 megatonnes.}}{{refn|group=note|On average somewhat over a million tonnes of CO<sub>2</sub> was emitted for every [[TWh]] of electricity generated in Turkey by coal-fired power stations in 2010.{{sfnp|Atilgan et al|2016|p=177}} This power station aims to generate just over 12.5 TWh (gross) per year.{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=xix|quote = \"y\u0131ll\u0131k ortalama br\u00fct 12.506 GWh, net 11.380 GWh enerji \u00fcretimi hedeflenmektedir.\" means \"targeted annual generation is 12,506 GWh gross, 11,380 GWh net\"}} The calculation in the EIA assumes an emission factor of 94.6 tCO2/TJ,{{sfnp|\u00c7\u0131nar|2020|p=319}} which is three times the average of 31 for Turkish lignite,{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2020|p=50}} but it is unclear whether this is the only reason the CO2 emissions per kWh are predicted to be very high compared to the 2010 average. Since 2020, more stringent filtering of local air pollutants from the smokestack has been compulsory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energy/coal/turkey-shuts-power-plants-for-not-installing-filters/27934|title=Turkey shuts power plants for not installing filters|publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|date=2020-01-02}}</ref> Moreover, although the average is about 2800,<ref name=SETA2019>{{cite report|title=Yerli\u0307 ve mi\u0307lli\u0307 enerji\u0307 poli\u0307ti\u0307kalari ekseni\u0307nde k\u00f6m\u00fcr |url=https://setav.org/assets/uploads/2019/01/A265.pdf |publisher=[[Foundation for Political, Economic and Social Research]]|date=January 2019}}</ref> the [[Heat of combustion#Lower heating value|net calorific value]] of Turkish lignite varies between 1000 and 6000 kcal/kg.{{sfnp|Turkstat report|2020|pages=59,60}}}} {{As of|2019}} coal mine methane remains a challenge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unece.org/info/media/news/sustainable-energy/2019/paving-the-way-for-safer-and-greener-coal-mine-methane-management-in-turkey-and-ukraine/doc.html|title=Paving the way for safer and greener coal mine methane management in Turkey and Ukraine|website=www.unece.org|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n===Water consumption===\nSome power stations in Zonguldak and Mu\u011fla consume large quantities of fresh water.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Thermal power plants in Zonguldak and Mu\u011fla leave nearby villages without water in the middle of a pandemic|url=https://www.duvarenglish.com/health-2/coronavirus/2020/04/13/thermal-power-plants-in-zonguldak-and-mugla-leave-nearby-villages-without-water-in-the-middle-of-a-pandemic/|website=www.duvarenglish.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-05-05}}</ref>\n\n==Consumption==\nThe amount of coal consumed in 2017 was more than a quarter higher than the amount in 2012, but coal made up about 30% of Turkey's primary energy in both years.<ref name=ClimateTransparency2019>{{Cite web|url=https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Managing-the-phase-out-of-coal-DIGITAL.pdf|title=Managing the Phase-out of Coal: A Comparison of Actions in G20 Countries|last=|first=|date=May 2019|website=Climate Transparency|access-date=2019-05-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524071757/https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Managing-the-phase-out-of-coal-DIGITAL.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2018 [[List of coal-fired power stations in Turkey|coal-fired power stations in Turkey]] burnt 80% of coal to generate electricity, 14% was used by industry, and 6% by buildings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://estore.enerdata.net/turkey-energy.html|title=Turkey energy market research {{!}} Turkey data, reports, prices|website=estore.enerdata.net|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> In 2018, 13 [[Tonne of oil equivalent|Mtoe]] of hard coal were used to generate electricity and heat; 4 Mtoe, in coke ovens; 2 Mtoe, for home heating; 2 Mtoe, in cement manufacture; and 1 Mtoe was used for iron and steel.<ref name=\"Energy Administration (2018)\">Energy Administration (2018)</ref> In 2018, 12 Mtoe of lignite were used to generate electricity and heat, 2 Mtoe in industry, and 1 Mtoe was used for home heating.<ref name=\"Energy Administration (2018)\" /> Lignite fired power stations did not become more productive between 2009 and 2018,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kasap|first=Ya\u015far|last2=\u015eens\u00f6\u011f\u00fct|first2=Cem|last3=\u00d6ren|first3=\u00d6zer|date=2020-03-01|title=Efficiency change of coal used for energy production in Turkey|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301420719308141|journal=Resources Policy|language=en|volume=65|pages=101577|doi=10.1016/j.resourpol.2019.101577|issn=0301-4207|doi-access=free}}</ref> but three-quarters by weight of coal burnt in Turkish power stations is lignite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yesilgazete.org/blog/2019/10/28/agustos-ayinda-termik-santrallerde-7-milyon-989-bin-ton-komur-yakildi/|title=A\u011fustos ay\u0131nda termik santrallerde 7 milyon 989 bin ton k\u00f6m\u00fcr yak\u0131ld\u0131|last=|first=|date=|website=Ye\u015fil Gazete|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\n==Subsidies==\n{{See also|Electricity sector in Turkey#Economics and finance}}\n\nAs a signatory of the [[Convention on Biological Diversity]] (Aichi Target 3), Turkey committed to phasing out environmentally harmful subsidies, including those to fossil fuels, by 2020.<ref>Doukas (2019), p. 2</ref> But coal remained the most subsidised source of electricity in Turkey.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yildizhan |first1=Hasan |title=Incentive policies for coal plants in Turkey |journal=Thermal Science |date=2017 |volume=21 |issue=5 |pages=1917\u20131924 |doi=10.2298/TSCI160428004Y |doi-access=free }}</ref> By 2020, according to [[Carbon Tracker]], both new wind and solar power were cheaper than building new coal power plants; and they forecast that wind would become cheaper than existing coal plants in 2027, and solar in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Maps_5_Logo.pdf|title=Wind vs Coal Power in Turkey/Solar PV vs Coal in Turkey|last=|first=|date=2020|website=[[Carbon Tracker]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318021148/https://carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Maps_5_Logo.pdf|archive-date=2020-03-18|access-date=}}</ref> Lignite-fired power stations receive multiple subsidies for construction<ref>{{cite web |title=Investment Guide > Investors' Guide > Incentives |url=http://www.invest.gov.tr/en-US/investmentguide/investorsguide/Pages/Incentives.aspx |website=Invest in Turkey |accessdate=19 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019205707/http://www.invest.gov.tr/en-US/investmentguide/investorsguide/Pages/Incentives.aspx |archive-date=19 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{refn|group=note|\"Metals\" described in the 4-b group of Article 2 of the current Mining Law No. 3213 include lignite thus lignite-fired power plants can receive region 5 subsidies regardless of their actual location in Turkey.}} and operation.<ref name=OECD>[http://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=FFS_TUR \"Fossil Fuel Support \u2013 TUR\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916205031/https://stats.oecd.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=FFS_TUR |date=2018-09-16 }}, OECD, accessed October 2018</ref> Specific subsidy programs include value-added tax waivers, offsetting investment costs and tax reductions.<ref name=TPQ2018>{{cite web |title=A New Strategy for EU-Turkey Energy Cooperation |url=http://turkishpolicy.com/article/938/a-new-strategy-for-eu-turkey-energy-cooperation |publisher=Turkish Policy Quarterly |date=27 November 2018 |access-date=21 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221230735/http://turkishpolicy.com/article/938/a-new-strategy-for-eu-turkey-energy-cooperation |archive-date=21 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Turkey's government support to coal and coal-fired power production and consumption \u20ba millions, 2016\u20132017 annual average <ref>Doukas (2019), p. 2</ref>\n!Instrument\n!Coal production\n!Coal-fired power\n!Coal consumption\n|-\n|Fiscal support (budgetary transfers and tax exemptions)\n|947\n|31\n|1,287\n|-\n|State-owned enterprise investment\n|198\n|953\n|none identified\n|}\n\nIn 2019, the Turkish government supported a bill to subsidize coal mining with multiple economic incentives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-05/18/c_138067631.htm|title=Turkish gov't submits draft bill for recovering incentives \u2013 Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> Mining and coal power plants are funded by the[[Turkey Wealth Fund]], but they do not describe it as a subsidy and they plan to pay dividends to the Treasury by 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/01/21/turkey-wealth-fund-eyes-becoming-strategic-investment-arm-of-the-country|title=Turkey Wealth Fund eyes becoming strategic investment arm of the country|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Sinan|date=2020-01-21|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===Capacity mechanism===\nIn 2019 [[List of power stations in Turkey#Coal|large lignite burning stations were subsidized]]  with [[Electricity market#Capacity market|capacity mechanism payments]] totalling almost 1 billion [[Turkish lira|lira]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/2019da-40-santrale-1-6-milyar-lira-destek-35998h.htm|title=Kapasite mekanizmas\u0131yla 2019\u2019da 40 santrale 1.6 milyar lira \u00f6dendi|date=2020-02-06|website=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milasonder.com/gundem/mucep-mugladaki-tum-termik-santraller-kapatilmalidir/48728|title=MU\u00c7EP: Mu\u011fla\u2019daki t\u00fcm termik santraller kapatilmalidir!|website=www.milasonder.com|language=tr|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204180955/https://www.milasonder.com/gundem/mucep-mugladaki-tum-termik-santraller-kapatilmalidir/48728|archive-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|In the neighbouring EU, by contrast, state aid to new coal power has been banned since 2019 and will be prohibited to existing coal power by 2025.}} Unlike new solar and wind power in Turkey's [[electricity market]], these were not decided by [[reverse auction]] but fixed by the government, and [[energy demand management]] is not eligible.<ref name=\"ResmiGazete30650\">{{cite web|url=http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2019/01/20190109-11.htm|title=Elektri\u0307k Pi\u0307yasasi Kapasi\u0307te Mekani\u0307zmasi Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307\u011fi\u0307nde De\u011fi\u0307\u015fi\u0307kli\u0307k Yapilmasina Dai\u0307r Y\u00f6netmeli\u0307k|date=9 January 2019|publisher=Official Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112143721/http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2019/01/20190109-11.htm|archive-date=12 January 2019|access-date=12 January 2019}}</ref> Subsidy continues in 2020 and 13 coal fired power stations received January payments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjiekonomisi.com/teias-yayinladi-kapasite-mekanizmasi-2020-yili-ocak-ayi-odeme-listesi/11668/|title=TE\u0130A\u015e Yay\u0131nlad\u0131: Kapasite Mekanizmas\u0131 2020 Y\u0131l\u0131 Ocak Ay\u0131 \u00d6deme Listesi|last=|first=|date=|website=Enerji Ekonomisi|language=tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nThe price of electricity generated from domestic coal is adjusted according to the [[consumer price index]], the [[producer price index]] and the dollar exchange rate, and paid by the [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|state-owned electricity company]] to private-sector power plants.<ref>{{cite news |title=K\u00f6m\u00fcr yerli ama \u00f6demesi dolarla |url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2019/ekonomi/komur-yerli-ama-odemesi-dolarla-3393380/ |work=S\u00f6zc\u00fc |date=5 February 2019 |access-date=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214002908/https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2019/ekonomi/komur-yerli-ama-odemesi-dolarla-3393380/ |archive-date=14 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Residential heating and cooking===\n[[File:Coal Stove - K\u00f6m\u00fcr Sobas\u0131.JPG|thumb|Coke stove exhibited in Ar\u0131kan House, [[Kozan, Adana|Kozan]].]]\nStarting from the 19th century stoves took the place of wood burning ovens in traditional Anatolian houses: for heating every room had a stove with a stovepipe or chimney. After the late 1970s [[Coke (fuel)|coke]] was reserved for use in institutions such as schools, and the more polluting but cheaper coal was supplied to households.  Imports of natural gas started in the late 1980s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Natural-Gas-Pipelines-and-Projects|title=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources - Natural Gas Pipelines and Projects|website=enerji.gov.tr|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and by the end of the 2010s the pipeline distribution network had been extended to over 80% of the population,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2020/01/05/total-inflow-to-turkish-gas-system-down-633-in-2019|title=Total inflow to Turkish gas system down 6.33% in 2019|last=AA|first=Daily Sabah with|date=2020-01-05|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> however due to [[energy poverty]] some of those people still used coal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paraanaliz.com/intelligence/household-gas-consumption-slumps-by-12-3-association-blames-it-on-global-warming/|title=Household gas consumption slumps by 12.3%, association blames it on global warming!|last=|first=|date=2019-04-20|website=PAIntelligence|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Thus most buildings constructed since the late 20th century have gas heating not coal. In the 2020s stoves burning coal and wood are still sometimes used for heating especially in rural areas, and even occasionally for cooking<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/messages/downloadsexceeded.html|title=Traditional Cooking Fuels, Ovens & Stoves in Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=citeseerx.ist.psu.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> although electricity and bottled gas are available everywhere. Free coal is supplied to households with average per person income less than one third of the minimum wage (less than 700TL in 2020) even in neighbourhoods which have piped gas.<ref>{{Cite web|title=K\u00f6m\u00fcr ve Yakacak Yard\u0131m\u0131 Ba\u015fvurusu Nas\u0131l Yap\u0131l\u0131r? Maddi Yard\u0131m 2020|url=https://www.finans365.com/komur-ve-yakacak-yardimi-basvurusu-nasil-yapilir-maddi-yardim-2020/14657/|last=|first=|date=|website=Finans 365|language=tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-05-06}}</ref> Indoor concentration of particulates is highest in the winter.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mentese|first=Sibel|last2=Mirici|first2=Nihal A.|last3=Otkun|first3=Muserref T.|last4=Bakar|first4=Coskun|last5=Palaz|first5=Elif|last6=Tasdibi|first6=Deniz|last7=Cevizci|first7=Sibel|last8=Cotuker|first8=Osman|date=2015-11-01|title=Association between respiratory health and indoor air pollution exposure in Canakkale, Turkey|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360132315000347|journal=Building and Environment|series=Special Issue: Indoor pollutants, chemistry and health- Selected papers presented at Indoor Air 2014 conference in Hong Kong|language=en|volume=93|pages=72\u201383|doi=10.1016/j.buildenv.2015.01.023|issn=0360-1323}}</ref> Over three quarters of [[Carbon monoxide poisoning|carbon monoxide deaths]] are due to stoves: almost 200 in 2017 mostly in poorer rural areas.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Can|first=G\u00fcnay|last2=Say\u0131l\u0131|first2=U\u011furcan|last3=Aksu Sayman|first3=\u00d6zden|last4=Kuyumcu|first4=\u00d6mer Faruk|last5=Y\u0131lmaz|first5=Duygu|last6=Esen|first6=Eren|last7=Yurtseven|first7=Eray|last8=Ergin\u00f6z|first8=Ethem|date=2019-01-03|title=Mapping of carbon monoxide related death risk in Turkey: a ten-year analysis based on news agency records|url=https://doi.org/10.1186/s12889-018-6342-4|journal=BMC Public Health|volume=19|issue=1|pages=9|doi=10.1186/s12889-018-6342-4|issn=1471-2458|pmc=6318903|pmid=30606153}}</ref>\n\n==Companies==\n\nBetween 2008 and 2018, coal was partially privatised;<ref name=\"GBR\">{{cite web |title=Turkey's 21st Century Coal Rush |url=https://www.gbreports.com/article/turkeys-21st-century-coal-rush |publisher=Global Business Reports |accessdate=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517131907/https://www.gbreports.com/article/turkeys-21st-century-coal-rush |archive-date=17 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> nevertheless state-owned companies mined over half of the total amount of Turkish coal in that year.<ref name=\"AA1\"/> [[Turkish Coal Operations Authority]] (TK\u0130) owns lignite mines, and [[Turkish Hard Coal Enterprises]] (TTK) owns hardcoal mines.\n\nSeveral companies have acquired mining rights for hard coal fields: Erdemir Madencilik, a subsidiary of Turkey's autonomous military pension program; Oyak; Tumas, a subsidiary of Bereket Holding, and energy company Emsa Enerji.<ref name=\"SPG2018\" /> In 2019 private companies paid over 20 million lira royalties to TTK.<ref>{{Cite web|title='Kara elmas'\u0131 g\u00fcn y\u00fcz\u00fcne \u00e7\u0131karan k\u00f6m\u00fcr firmalar\u0131 TTK'ye de kazand\u0131r\u0131yor|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/tr/ekonomi/kara-elmasi-gun-yuzune-cikaran-komur-firmalari-ttkye-de-kazandiriyor/1821268|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2020-05-07}}</ref> Lignite fields have been transferred to Imbat Madencilik, Fernas Holding, Demir Export and construction group Yapi Tek.<ref name=GBR/> Another company, Polyak Eynez, is developing a hard lignite mine near \u0130zmir that is planned to be the deepest in the country<ref>{{cite book|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=34|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> and an associated power plant.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://www.finaenerji.com/about-us/ |publisher=Fina Enerji |accessdate=17 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517145657/https://www.finaenerji.com/about-us/ |archive-date=17 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Eren Holding]] holds the largest amount of coal-fired generation capacity, 2,790 megawatts,<ref>{{cite web |title=Energy |url=http://www.erenholding.com.tr/en/sectors/energy |publisher=Eren Holding |accessdate=27 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228175655/http://www.erenholding.com.tr/en/sectors/energy |archive-date=28 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> at the ZETES power complex in Zonguldak. Several companies hold more than a gigawatt of coal power capacity: IC I\u00e7ta\u015f Enerji, the state-owned [[Electricity Generation Company (Turkey)|Electricity Generation Company]] (E\u00dcA\u015e); Konya \u015eeker, a company owned by Anadolu Birlik Holding; ERG Elektrik; Diler Holding; \u00c7elikler Holding and Ciner Holding.<ref name=Carbtrkfullrep2018/> However, mining licence information that is held by the government in the \"e-maden\" database is not released to the public.<ref>{{cite news |title=\"Madenleri olan\" de\u011fil verimli i\u015fleyen kazan\u0131r! |url=https://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/sedat-yilmaz/madenleri-olan-degil-verimli-isleyen-kazanir-27097.html |publisher=Yeni Akit |accessdate=11 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111041629/https://www.yeniakit.com.tr/yazarlar/sedat-yilmaz/madenleri-olan-degil-verimli-isleyen-kazanir-27097.html |archive-date=11 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2010s, the government attempted to auction mine licenses to private companies provided that they would build nearby power plants,<ref name=GBR/> but the auctions attracted little interest<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://350.org/sweet-dreams-are-made-of-this-turkeys-coal-to-disagree/|title=Sweet dreams are made of this: Turkey's coal to disagree|website=350.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720143626/https://350.org/sweet-dreams-are-made-of-this-turkeys-coal-to-disagree/|archive-date=2019-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref> as the currency weakened.<ref>{{Cite report|url=https://endcoal.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/BoomAndBust_2020_English.pdf|title=Boom and Bust 2020: Tracking the Global Coal Plant Pipeline|last=Shearer|first=Christine|last2=Myllyvirta|first2=Lauri|date=March 2020|publisher=[[Global Energy Monitor]]|url-status=live|last3=Yu|first3=Aiqun|last4=Aitken|first4=Greig|last5=Mathew-Shah|first5=Neha|last6=Dallos|first6=Gyorgy|last7=Nace|first7=Ted}}</ref> Also at that time the government tried to re-privatize the 290-MW Yunus Emre power station, but it remains publicly owned. And although lignite is more polluting than most other types of coal, the government tried to persuade other coal-fired power stations to convert to lignite to reduce import costs.<ref name=SP2019>{{cite news |title=Economic Issues to Weigh on Turkish Market |url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/010319-outlook-2019-european-thermal-coal-market-looks-to-china-for-direction-in-year-ahead |publisher=S & P Global: Platts |date=3 January 2019 |access-date=6 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190106153609/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/010319-outlook-2019-european-thermal-coal-market-looks-to-china-for-direction-in-year-ahead |archive-date=6 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Turkish currency and debt crisis, 2018|2018 Turkish currency crisis]] and 2020 [[coronavirus recession]]{{Citation needed|date=May 2020}} increased costs for mining companies and increased the difficulty of obtaining bank credits, threatening the coal industry.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=9|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Turkish energy companies owe over US$50 billion to banks. In particular, Anadolu Birlik Holding holds $1 billion in debt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-23/turkey-s-anadolu-birlik-said-to-seek-energy-loan-restructuring|title=One of Turkey's Largest Food Producers Seeks Loan Restructuring|date=23 January 2019|access-date=4 February 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207022445/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-23/turkey-s-anadolu-birlik-said-to-seek-energy-loan-restructuring|archive-date=7 February 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]}}</ref>\n\n===International investments===\n\nTurkish company Y\u0131lmaden has acquired [[Mineral industry of Colombia#Coal|coal mining rights in Colombia]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Turkey Mining 2018|publisher=Global Business Reports|page=58|url=https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|access-date=2019-05-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517135330/https://www.gbreports.com/files/pdf/_2018/Turkey_Mining_2018_-_Web_Version.pdf|archive-date=2019-05-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Companies based in Turkey are building coal-fired power stations in other countries such as [[Sri Lanka]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/09/29/ceb-strikes-another-blow-at-the-countrys-economy-with-uncessary-power-purchase/|title=A 4th coal power plant for Sri Lanka? \u2013 Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2019-09-29|website=Sri Lanka News \u2013 Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=2019-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003114015/https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/09/29/ceb-strikes-another-blow-at-the-countrys-economy-with-uncessary-power-purchase/|archive-date=2019-10-03|url-status=live}}</ref> and the national exim bank is still prepared to finance coal power if it is Ultra Super Critical with emissions <750g CO2/kWh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ieefa.org/finance-exiting-coal/|title=Over 100 and counting|website=Institute for Energy Economics & Financial Analysis|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> [[State-owned enterprises of China|Chinese state owned enterprises]] and companies investing in coal power projects<ref>OECD (2019), p. 36</ref> include [[Shanghai Electric Power]], which is the main investor in the [[Emba Hunutlu power station]] under construction in [[Adana Province]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey sees a sudden spike in Chinese investments through 'Belt and Road Initiative' |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2018/06/30/turkey-sees-a-sudden-spike-in-chinese-investments-through-belt-and-road-initiative |work=Daily Sabah |date=30 June 2018 |accessdate=1 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024152704/https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2018/06/30/turkey-sees-a-sudden-spike-in-chinese-investments-through-belt-and-road-initiative |archive-date=24 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Xinhua\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/23/c_138413218.htm|title=China's power plant project with direct investment in Turkey starts construction|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2019-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925164515/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/23/c_138413218.htm|archive-date=2019-09-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Imports==\n[[File:Coal Balance Turkey.svg|thumb|Much of the rise in consumption in the 21st century was due to the construction of coastal power stations burning imported hard coal.]]\nIn 2019 about 32 million tonnes was imported,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montelnews.com/en/story/turkey-coal-imports-surge-20-amid-lignite-plant-suspensions/1093459|title=Turkey coal imports surge 20% amid lignite plant suspensions|website=www.montelnews.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> 3% of the world's coal,<ref name=ClimateTransparency2019/> and in 2018 US$4.4 billion was spent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/incentives-to-speed-up-returns-on-turkish-rooftop-solar-150045|title=Incentives to speed up returns on Turkish rooftop solar - Latest News|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221155109/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/incentives-to-speed-up-returns-on-turkish-rooftop-solar-150045|archive-date=2019-12-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Imported coal generates about a quarter of the nation's electricity:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2020/ekonomi/turkiyenin-komur-aski-bitmiyor-5611118/|title=T\u00fcrkiye'nin k\u00f6m\u00fcr a\u015fk\u0131 bitmiyor|website=www.sozcu.com.tr|language=tr|access-date=2020-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207131713/https://www.sozcu.com.tr/2020/ekonomi/turkiyenin-komur-aski-bitmiyor-5611118/|archive-date=2020-02-07|url-status=live}}</ref> more than local coal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/09/17/turkeys-daily-wind-power-generation-sets-record|title=Turkey's daily wind power generation sets record|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-09-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927124116/https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2019/09/17/turkeys-daily-wind-power-generation-sets-record|archive-date=2019-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[European Union\u2013Turkey Customs Union|customs union deal with the EU]] includes bilateral trade concessions on coal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Updating customs union with EU is priority: Turkish Finance Minister |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/updating-customs-union-with-eu-is-priority-turkish-finance-minister-141557 |work=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228214042/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/updating-customs-union-with-eu-is-priority-turkish-finance-minister-141557 |archive-date=28 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The largest supplier in 2019 was Colombia with 17.5 Mt followed by Russia with 12.35 Mt.{{Citation needed|date=May 2020}}  Russian coal may become more competitive when improvements to Russia's [[Taman, Russia#Port Taman|Taman Port]] on the Black Sea coast are completed in 2020, or when some contracts expire in 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/102119-bearish-mood-for-us-colombian-participants-at-coaltrans-event-sources|title=Bearish mood for US, Colombian participants at Coaltrans event: sources {{!}} S&P Global Platts|date=2019-10-21|website=www.spglobal.com|access-date=2019-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101141938/https://www.spglobal.com/platts/en/market-insights/latest-news/coal/102119-bearish-mood-for-us-colombian-participants-at-coaltrans-event-sources|archive-date=2019-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019}}, the largest supplier of [[Metallurgical coal|coking coal]] is Australia, and [[Coke (fuel)|met coke]] is imported from Russia and China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey boosts imports of coking coal from US, Canada |url=https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/1900507-turkey-boosts-imports-of-coking-coal-from-us-canada |publisher=Argus Media |date=10 May 2019 |access-date=24 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524070027/https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/1900507-turkey-boosts-imports-of-coking-coal-from-us-canada |archive-date=24 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{As of|2018}} if the import price of thermal coal is less than 70 US$/tonne ([[free on board|fob]]) the state charges the difference as import duty.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|title=Energy pricing and non-market flows in Turkey's energy sector|last=|first=|date=|website=SHURA Energy Transition Center|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230104503/https://www.shura.org.tr/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/raporweb_ENG.pdf|archive-date=2019-12-30|access-date=}}</ref> {{As of|2020|}} coking coal costs around US$130/tonne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.argusmedia.com/en/news/2090040-atlantic-coking-coal-focus-turns-to-logistics|title=Atlantic coking coal: Focus turns to logistics|date=2020-03-24|website=www.argusmedia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> There are bilateral trade concessions with the EU on coal products.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/business/calculation-customs-duties/rules-origin/customs-unions/turkey-customs-unions-preferential-arrangements_en|title=Turkey : Customs Unions and preferential arrangements|last=Anonymous|date=2016-09-13|website=Taxation and Customs Union - European Commission|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203221841/https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/business/calculation-customs-duties/rules-origin/customs-unions/turkey-customs-unions-preferential-arrangements_en|archive-date=2020-02-03|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Anthracite]] coal from [[Donbass]], a region in Ukraine, is exported (allegedly illegally) to Turkey. The anthracite is transported through the Russian ports of [[Azov]] and [[Taganrog]] to the Turkish city of [[Samsun]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Russia's Hybrid Strategy in the Sea of Azov: Divide and Antagonize (Part Two) |url=https://jamestown.org/program/russias-hybrid-strategy-in-the-sea-of-azov-divide-and-antagonize-part-two/ |website=Eurasia Daily Monitor Volume: 16 Issue: 18 |publisher=Jamestown Foundation |accessdate=13 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213082517/https://jamestown.org/program/russias-hybrid-strategy-in-the-sea-of-azov-divide-and-antagonize-part-two/ |archive-date=13 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n{{As of|2020||df=}} the CEO of the sovereign wealth fund wants to invest in coal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ecffb6d6-4f2c-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|title=Turkey wealth fund chief rebuffs criticism of Erdogan's role|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ft.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221142807/https://www.ft.com/content/ecffb6d6-4f2c-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5|archive-date=2020-02-21|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> According to \u00dcmit \u015eahin, who teaches climate change at [[Sabanc\u0131 University]], Turkey is not facing up to the reality that most coal will have to be left in the ground and risks losing access to international [[Climate Finance|climate finance]] if the country does not quickly schedule an exit from coal.\n\nMany local communities strongly oppose coal power stations<ref>{{Cite book|last=Turhan|first=Ethemcan|url=https://www.oapen.org/download?type=document&docid=1005506|title=Transforming Socio-Natures in Turkey: Landscapes, State and Environmental Movements|last2=\u00d6zkaynak|first2=Beg\u00fcm|last3=Ayd\u0131n|first3=Cem \u0130skender|publisher=|year=2020|isbn=978-0-429-42969-9|location=|pages=}}</ref> and mines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yesilgazete.org/blog/2020/02/05/derekoy-yaylasina-maden-ocagi-girisimi-koyluleri-ayaga-kaldirdi/|title=Derek\u00f6y Yaylas\u0131'na maden oca\u011f\u0131 giri\u015fimi k\u00f6yl\u00fcleri aya\u011fa kald\u0131rd\u0131|date=2020-02-05|website=Ye\u015fil Gazete - ekolojik, politik, kat\u0131l\u0131mc\u0131, \u015fenlikli...|language=tr-TR|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> for example by legal action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.korfezgazete.com/hataydaki-cevre-koruma-dernekleri-305-maden-sahasinin-iptalini-talep-etti/|title=Hatay'daki \u00c7evre Koruma Dernekleri 305 Maden Sahas\u0131n\u0131n \u0130ptalini Talep Etti {{!}} K\u00f6rfez Gazetesi|last=Haber|first=Korfezgazete|language=tr|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> From the late 2000s, residents of Amasra strongly fought against the establishment of a coal-fired power station near the city and it was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Regional Briefings for the 2018 Coal Plant Developers List |url=https://coalexit.org/sites/default/files/inline-files/Regional%20Briefings%20CPDL_10-04-2018_final.pdf |work=Coalexit |date=2018 |access-date=2018-12-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412013642/https://coalexit.org/sites/default/files/inline-files/Regional%20Briefings%20CPDL_10-04-2018_final.pdf |archive-date=2019-04-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[Alpu]] district, locals of the region won a court battle in 2018 to prevent the building of a new coal mine; the 14th chamber of the [[Council of State (Turkey)|Council of State]] ruled that the mine could only be built with an environmental report.<ref>{{cite news |title=Court says 'environment report necessary' for planned coal mine in western Turkey |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/court-says-environment-report-necessary-for-planned-new-coal-mine-in-western-turkey-135665 |work=Demir\u00f6ren News Agency |date=10 August 2018 |access-date=26 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016164949/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/court-says-environment-report-necessary-for-planned-new-coal-mine-in-western-turkey-135665 |archive-date=16 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkish activists have also taken their campaign to international conferences.<ref>{{cite news |title=Climate change: Governments don't act? We do! |url=https://www.dw.com/en/climate-change-governments-dont-act-we-do/a-46744981 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=14 December 2018 |access-date=18 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219000851/https://www.dw.com/en/climate-change-governments-dont-act-we-do/a-46744981 |archive-date=19 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nevertheless, in 2019 only 36 of the 600 members of [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|parliament]] voted to reduce power plant emission limits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birgun.net/haber/termik-santrallarin-gercek-bedeli-olum-277431|title=Termik santrallar\u0131n ger\u00e7ek bedeli \u00f6l\u00fcm|website=birgun.net|language=Turkish|access-date=2020-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131110419/https://www.birgun.net/haber/termik-santrallarin-gercek-bedeli-olum-277431|archive-date=2020-01-31|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Coal phase-out ==\n\nFive old plants ([[Af\u015fin-Elbistan power stations|Af\u015fin-Elbistan A]], [[Seyit\u00f6mer power station|Seyit\u00f6mer]], Tun\u00e7bilek, [[Kangal power station|Kangal]] and  \u00c7atala\u011fz\u0131) were closed in 2020 because they did not meet new pollution limits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-turkiye-50969252|title=Filtre takt\u0131rmayan ve baca gaz\u0131 ar\u0131tma \u00f6nlemi almayan 5 termik santral tamamen kapat\u0131ld\u0131|date=2020-01-02|access-date=2020-01-02|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112085934/https://www.bbc.com/turkce/haberler-turkiye-50969252|archive-date=2020-01-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The country is the world's ninth-largest consumer of coal, similar to Poland and Germany, but Germany has more developed plans for a [[coal phase-out]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sartor |first1=O. |title=Implementing coal transitions Insights from case studies of major coal-consuming economies |date=2018 |publisher=IDDRI and Climate Strategies. |url=https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/coal_synthesis_final.pdf |access-date=2018-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025225556/https://coaltransitions.files.wordpress.com/2018/09/coal_synthesis_final.pdf |archive-date=2018-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> \u2013 an area for planned cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey, Germany agree to join forces for new energy, industry projects |url=https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/27/turkey-germany-agree-to-join-forces-for-new-energy-industry-projects |work=Daily Sabah |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027003225/https://www.dailysabah.com/energy/2018/10/27/turkey-germany-agree-to-join-forces-for-new-energy-industry-projects |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In terms of energy resources, Spain is more similar, having hydropower and abundant sunshine, and its transition away from coal could also be a model.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain to close most coalmines in \u20ac250m transition deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/oct/26/spain-to-close-most-coal-mines-after-striking-250m-deal |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 October 2018 |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027061514/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/oct/26/spain-to-close-most-coal-mines-after-striking-250m-deal |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Turkish industry has experience converting coal to solar outside the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefifthestate.com.au/energy-lead/energy/eastern-europe-shows-how-to-convert-coal-to-solar/|title=Eastern Europe shows how to convert coal to solar|date=2020-03-03|website=The Fifth Estate|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[OECD]] said that Turkey's coal-fired power plant development programme is creating a high [[carbon lock-in]] risk due to the large [[capital cost]]s and long infrastructure lifetimes.<ref>OECD (2019), p. 40</ref> It also stated that energy and climate policies that are not aligned in future may prevent some assets from providing an economic return due to the transition to a [[low-carbon economy]].<ref>OECD (2019), p. 39</ref> Additionally, new wind or solar power is forecast to be cheaper than new coal-fired power plants by 2022 by the think tank [[Carbon Tracker]]. The average Turkish coal-fired power station is predicted to have higher long-run operating costs than new renewables by 2023<ref name=Carbtrkfullrep2018>{{cite web |title=Powering down coal: Navigating the economic and financial risks in the last years of coal power |url=https://www.carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/CTI_Powering_Down_Coal_Report_Nov_2018-1.pdf |publisher=[[Carbon Tracker Initiative]] |date=November 2018 |access-date=2018-12-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223121215/https://www.carbontracker.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/CTI_Powering_Down_Coal_Report_Nov_2018-1.pdf |archive-date=2018-12-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> and all renewables by 2030.<ref name=\"Carbtrk2018\">{{cite web |title=Powering down coal: Navigating the economic and financial risks in the last years of coal power |url=https://www.carbontracker.org/reports/coal-portal/ |publisher=[[Carbon Tracker Initiative]] |accessdate=30 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181201005020/https://www.carbontracker.org/reports/coal-portal/ |archive-date=1 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> As lignite power plants tend to be inland replacing them with solar or wind power could save water.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.triplepundit.com/story/2019/wind-could-power-30-percent-global-electricity-production-2050/85796/|title=Wind Could Provide 30 Percent of Global Electricity By 2050|website=www.triplepundit.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191215090204/https://www.triplepundit.com/story/2019/wind-could-power-30-percent-global-electricity-production-2050/85796/|archive-date=2019-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Employment===\nBy the end of 2017, the renewable energy industry employed 84,000 people,<ref>{{cite web |title=How Turkey Can Ensure a Successful Energy Transition |url=https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/security/reports/2018/07/10/453281/turkey-can-ensure-successful-energy-transition/ |publisher=Center for American Progress |accessdate=19 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063254/https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/security/reports/2018/07/10/453281/turkey-can-ensure-successful-energy-transition/ |archive-date=20 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> whereas coal mining employed 10,000 in 13 public-sector workplaces and 26,000 in 430 private-sector workplaces.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maden \u0130statistikleri |url=http://mapeg.gov.tr/maden_istatistik.aspx |publisher=MAPEG |accessdate=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222204844/http://mapeg.gov.tr/maden_istatistik.aspx |archive-date=22 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2019, the minimum wage for coal miners was 4,059 lira (US$700) per month, twice the standard minimum wage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Changes to minimum wage, severance payments and administrative fines |url=https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Employment-Benefits/Turkey/Gn-Partners/Changes-to-minimum-wage-severance-payments-and-administrative-fines |publisher=G\u00fcn and Partners |accessdate=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213080534/https://www.internationallawoffice.com/Newsletters/Employment-Benefits/Turkey/Gn-Partners/Changes-to-minimum-wage-severance-payments-and-administrative-fines |archive-date=13 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nDue to the complex geology of the [[Zonguldak basin]], hardcoal production in Turkey is insignificant, heavily subsidised and labour-intensive.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey: country profile |url=https://euracoal.eu/info/country-profiles/turkey/ |publisher=Euracoal |accessdate=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027232015/https://euracoal.eu/info/country-profiles/turkey/ |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, [[Zonguldak Province]] is highly dependent on coal:<ref>{{cite book |last1=ERGEN |first1=Mustafa |title=A New Methodology Proposal for Urban Regeneration of Brownfield Areas; Case Study of Zonguldak City, Turkey|date=7 March 2013 |url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/46912647.pdf |access-date=27 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027190701/https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/46912647.pdf |archive-date=27 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of|2018|lc=y}}, most working men in [[Zonguldak]] city were employed in the coal industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2018/10/05/absolute-darkness-a-day-in-a-miners-life|title=Absolute darkness: A day in a miner's life|website=DailySabah|access-date=2019-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720135706/https://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2018/10/05/absolute-darkness-a-day-in-a-miners-life|archive-date=2019-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this, {{As of|2020||lc=y}}, Turkey had not implemented a [[Just Transition|just transition]] policy, although the government spoke in favor of it in 2015.<ref name=\"ClimateTransparency2019\" /> Three coal-fired power plants, which are in [[Mu\u011fla Province]], [[Yata\u011fan power station|Yata\u011fan]], Yenik\u00f6y and Kemerk\u00f6y, are becoming outdated. Currently, the old plants need refurbishment to meet forthcoming local air pollution limits. [[Climate Action Network]] Europe recommends shutting them down instead of refurbishing them if the subsidies are redeployed locally as the most economically feasible option. However, if the plants and associated lignite mines were shut down, about 5000 workers would need funding for early retirement or retraining.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Real Costs of Coal: Mu\u011fla|url=http://costsofcoal.caneurope.org/ |publisher=[[Climate Action Network]] Europe |accessdate=25 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126001032/http://costsofcoal.caneurope.org/ |archive-date=26 January 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There would also be health and environmental benefits, but these are difficult to quantify as very little official data is released on the local pollution by the plants and mines.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Turkey|Global Warming}}\n\n* {{annotated link|Environmental issues in Turkey}}\n* {{annotated link|Greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey}}\n* {{annotated link|Glossary of coal mining terminology}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite report  \n |work=[[Turkish Statistical Institute]]\n |title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory report [TurkStat report]\n |date=April 2020\n |url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/tur-2020-nir-13apr20.zip\n }}\n\n*{{cite web  \n |work=[[Turkish Statistical Institute]]\n |title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory 1990 - 2018 common reporting format (CRF) tables [Tu